// German v2 Unit 16 — Arabic source language (srcLang:"ar")
// Auto-generated. Fields marked [AR] need manual Arabic translation.
const UNIT_16_AR = {n:16,lang:"de",srcLang:"ar",track:"v2",title:"Der Streit",sub:"Neighbor conflict, Ruhezeit, indirect questions, nachdem + Plusquamperfekt",icon:"📝",level:"B1.2",color:"#7B5EE8",lessons:[
    {id:"deu_r16l1",title:"Das Bohrloch",icon:"🔩",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Das Bohrloch",desc:"[AR] Sunday evening, 20:05. Verumius has a drill and a shelf. What could go wrong? A lot, if you do not know the Ruhezeit (quiet hours).",goals:[
            "[AR] Learn vocabulary for arguments, conflicts, and emotions",
            "[AR] Discover the German Ruhezeit and Hausordnung",
            "[AR] Experience Verumius's first neighbor dispute"
          ]},
        {type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"scene-setting",art:"de-ber-apartment-drill",trg:"Sonntagabend, 20:05 Uhr. Verumius hat eine Bohrmaschine in der Hand und ein Regal an der Wand. Alles ist ruhig. Fast.",src:"[AR] Sunday evening, 8:05 PM. Verumius has a drill in his hand and a shelf on the wall. Everything is quiet. Almost."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Bohrmaschine",src:"[AR] the drill, the power drill",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Feminine noun. Bohren (to drill) + Maschine (machine).\nThe central prop of every German neighbor dispute.",example:"A: Brauchst du die Bohrmaschine?\nB: Ja, aber nicht am Sonntag.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Do you need the drill?\nB: Yes, but not on Sunday.",funFact:"[AR] In Germany, using a Bohrmaschine on a Sunday or during Ruhezeit (quiet hours) is a serious offense. Neighbor disputes involving drills are a beloved German sitcom cliche."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Streit",src:"[AR] the argument, the dispute",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] Covers everything from a small quarrel to a legal dispute.\nEinen Streit haben = to have an argument.",example:"A: Hattest du einen Streit mit dem Nachbarn?\nB: Ja, er war sehr laut.\nA: Was war das Problem?\nB: Ich habe am Sonntag gebohrt.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Did you have an argument with the neighbor?\nB: Yes, he was very loud.\nA: What was the problem?\nB: I drilled on Sunday.",funFact:"[AR] From Old High German 'strit' (battle). The word covers everything from a lovers' quarrel to a legal dispute. 'Einen Streit haben' is heard in every German apartment building."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Ärger",src:"[AR] the annoyance, the trouble",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] Related to 'arg' (bad). Trouble, annoyance, anger in one word.\nÄrger machen = to cause trouble.",example:"A: Was ist los? Du siehst gestresst aus.\nB: Ich habe Ärger mit dem Nachbarn.\nA: Schon wieder?\nB: Ja, wegen der Ruhezeit.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: What's wrong? You look stressed.\nB: I have trouble with the neighbor.\nA: Again?\nB: Yes, because of the quiet hours.",funFact:"[AR] Related to 'arg' (bad/severe). Der Ärger is trouble, annoyance, and anger rolled into one. The Umlaut dots make it hiss like frustration itself."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Konflikt",src:"[AR] the conflict",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] Borrowed from Latin 'conflictus' (a striking together).\nA Streit can be small; a Konflikt is structural.",example:"A: Gibt es einen Konflikt im Haus?\nB: Ja, zwischen dem zweiten und dritten Stock.\nA: Was für ein Konflikt?\nB: Lärm am Wochenende.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Is there a conflict in the building?\nB: Yes, between the second and third floor.\nA: What kind of conflict?\nB: Noise on the weekend.",funFact:"[AR] Borrowed from Latin 'conflictus' (a striking together). Germans use it for serious disputes. A Streit can be small; a Konflikt is structural. Office politics, international relations, neighbor wars."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Laune",src:"[AR] the mood",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Gute Laune = good mood. Schlechte Laune = bad mood.\nLaunisch = moody.",example:"A: Wie ist deine Laune heute?\nB: Schlechte Laune. Der Nachbar hat geklopft.\nA: Das verdirbt die Laune.\nB: Ja, total.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: How is your mood today?\nB: Bad mood. The neighbor knocked.\nA: That ruins the mood.\nB: Yes, totally.",funFact:"[AR] From Latin 'luna' (moon). The idea that moods change like moon phases. 'Launisch' means moody. Germans track moods like weather forecasts."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Stimmung",src:"[AR] the atmosphere, the mood",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] From 'Stimme' (voice). The mood a group or room creates.\nCommon usage: 'The vibe is right' (Die Stimmung ist gut).",example:"A: Wie war die Stimmung auf der Party?\nB: Am Anfang gut, dann gab es Streit.\nA: Oh nein. Worüber?\nB: Über die Musik. Zu laut.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: How was the atmosphere at the party?\nB: Good at first, then there was an argument.\nA: Oh no. About what?\nB: About the music. Too loud.",funFact:"[AR] From 'Stimme' (voice). The mood that a group or room creates together. Concert reviews always discuss Stimmung. A word that captures the collective emotional temperature."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Nerv",src:"[AR] the nerve",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] Plural: Nerven. Du gehst mir auf die Nerven = You are getting on my nerves.",example:"A: Der Lärm geht mir auf die Nerven!\nB: Welcher Lärm?\nA: Die Bohrmaschine von oben!\nB: Das ist Verumius. Er bohrt seit einer Stunde.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The noise is getting on my nerves!\nB: What noise?\nA: The drill from upstairs!\nB: That's Verumius. He's been drilling for an hour.",funFact:"[AR] 'Du gehst mir auf die Nerven' is THE German complaint phrase. Borrowed from Latin 'nervus.' Every neighbor dispute involves Nerven. Plural always: you never lose just one nerve."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"neighbor",mood:"irritated",art:"de-ber-apartment-ceiling",trg:"Im zweiten Stock saß Herr Kellermann vor seinem Fernseher. Tatort lief. Dann kam das Bohren. An einem Sonntag. Um 20:05.",src:"[AR] On the second floor, Mr. Kellermann sat in front of his TV. Tatort was on. Then came the drilling. On a Sunday. At 8:05 PM."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Sorge",src:"[AR] the worry, the concern",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Keine Sorge! = No worries! Sich Sorgen machen = to worry.\nFeminine, like most abstract nouns ending in -e.",example:"A: Ich mache mir Sorgen wegen des Streits.\nB: Keine Sorge, das wird schon.\nA: Meinst du?\nB: Ja, sprich einfach mit dem Nachbarn.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: I'm worried about the argument.\nB: No worries, it will be fine.\nA: You think so?\nB: Yes, just talk to the neighbor.",funFact:"[AR] 'Keine Sorge!' (No worries!) is comforting. 'Sich Sorgen machen' uses the reflexive. Die Sorge is feminine, like most abstract nouns ending in -e."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Vorwurf",src:"[AR] the accusation, the reproach",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] Vor (before) + Wurf (throw). You throw something in front of someone.\nJemandem Vorwürfe machen = to accuse someone.",example:"A: Der Nachbar macht mir Vorwürfe.\nB: Warum?\nA: Weil ich zu laut war.\nB: Hat er recht?",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbor is making accusations.\nB: Why?\nA: Because I was too loud.\nB: Is he right?",funFact:"[AR] Vor (before) + Wurf (throw). You throw something in front of someone. 'Jemandem Vorwürfe machen' is the classic weapon in any German Streit."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Vorschrift",src:"[AR] the regulation, the rule",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Vor (before) + Schrift (writing). Something written beforehand.\nDie Hausordnung is a book of Vorschriften.",example:"A: Kennst du die Vorschriften im Haus?\nB: Nein, welche Vorschriften?\nA: Die Ruhezeit! Kein Lärm nach 20 Uhr.\nB: Das wusste ich nicht!",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Do you know the regulations in the building?\nB: No, what regulations?\nA: The quiet hours! No noise after 8 PM.\nB: I didn't know that!",funFact:"[AR] Vor (before) + Schrift (writing). Something written down beforehand. Germans are famous for Vorschriften. The Hausordnung (house rules) is a book of Vorschriften."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"das Verbot",src:"[AR] the prohibition, the ban",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"[AR] From 'verbieten' (to forbid). A Verbot is absolute.\nRauchverbot = smoking ban. Parkverbot = no parking.",example:"A: Gibt es ein Verbot für Lärm?\nB: Ja, während der Ruhezeit.\nA: Was passiert, wenn man das Verbot ignoriert?\nB: Man bekommt eine Warnung oder Strafe.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Is there a ban on noise?\nB: Yes, during the quiet hours.\nA: What happens if you ignore the ban?\nB: You get a warning or a fine.",funFact:"[AR] From 'verbieten' (to forbid). A Verbot is absolute: no exceptions. 'Rauchverbot' (smoking ban), 'Parkverbot' (no parking). German compounds with Verbot are everywhere."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Strafe",src:"[AR] the punishment, the penalty",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Zur Strafe = as punishment. Geldstrafe = fine.\nHaftstrafe = prison sentence.",example:"A: Gibt es eine Strafe für Lärm am Sonntag?\nB: Theoretisch ja, eine Geldstrafe.\nA: Wie viel?\nB: Bis zu fünfhundert Euro.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Is there a penalty for noise on Sunday?\nB: Theoretically yes, a fine.\nA: How much?\nB: Up to five hundred euros.",funFact:"[AR] Geldstrafe = fine. Haftstrafe = prison sentence. The Ruhezeit violation Verumius just committed? In theory, a Strafe-worthy offense. In practice, usually just an angry note."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"panicking",art:"de-ber-apartment-drill-stopped",trg:"Das Regal hing schief. Aber die Uhr zeigte 20:15. Ich legte die Bohrmaschine hin. Dann hörte ich Schritte im Treppenhaus. Langsame, wütende Schritte.",src:"[AR] The shelf hung crooked. But the clock showed 8:15 PM. I put down the drill. Then I heard footsteps in the stairwell. Slow, angry footsteps."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"wütend",src:"[AR] furious, angry",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'Wut' (rage). Stronger than ärgerlich.\nWütend werden = to become furious.",example:"A: Der Nachbar ist wütend.\nB: Warum?\nA: Wegen der Bohrmaschine.\nB: Kann ich verstehen. Es ist Sonntagabend.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbor is furious.\nB: Why?\nA: Because of the drill.\nB: I can understand. It's Sunday evening.",funFact:"[AR] From 'Wut' (rage). Stronger than ärgerlich. 'Wütend werden' means to become furious. The neighbor above is probably wütend right now."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"ärgerlich",src:"[AR] annoying, irritating",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] From Ärger. Can describe the annoyed person OR the annoying thing.\nCommon usage: 'That is annoying' (Das ist ärgerlich).",example:"A: Das ist wirklich ärgerlich.\nB: Was ist ärgerlich?\nA: Die Situation mit dem Nachbarn.\nB: Ja, aber du bist auch ärgerlich für ihn.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: That is really annoying.\nB: What is annoying?\nA: The situation with the neighbor.\nB: Yes, but you are also annoying to him.",funFact:"[AR] Can describe the person who is annoyed OR the thing that causes annoyance. 'Das ist ärgerlich' (That is annoying). Dual meaning, context decides."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"ernst",src:"[AR] serious",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Im Ernst? = Seriously? Also a common first name.\nCommon usage: 'The situation is serious' (Die Lage ist ernst).",example:"A: Ist die Situation ernst?\nB: Ja, der Nachbar will die Polizei rufen.\nA: Im Ernst?\nB: Ja, im Ernst.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Is the situation serious?\nB: Yes, the neighbor wants to call the police.\nA: Seriously?\nB: Yes, seriously.",funFact:"[AR] 'Im Ernst?' (Seriously?) is everyday speech. Also a common first name (Ernst). 'Die Lage ist ernst' is how German news anchors begin bad news."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"still",src:"[AR] quiet, silent",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Sei still! = Be quiet! Stilles Wasser = non-carbonated water.\nStille Nacht = Silent Night (the Christmas carol).",example:"A: Sei still! Der Nachbar schläft.\nB: Aber es ist erst acht Uhr!\nA: Ruhezeit. Alles muss still sein.\nB: In Deutschland ist sonntags alles still.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Be quiet! The neighbor is sleeping.\nB: But it's only eight o'clock!\nA: Quiet hours. Everything must be silent.\nB: In Germany everything is quiet on Sundays.",funFact:"[AR] 'Sei still!' (Be quiet!) is what every German child hears. Also: 'Stille Nacht' (Silent Night), the Christmas carol written in Austria. Still water = Stilles Wasser (non-carbonated)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"schreien",src:"[AR] to scream, to shout",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: schrie, geschrien. Same root as English 'shriek'.\nSchrei nicht so! = Don't shout like that!",example:"A: Der Nachbar schreit!\nB: Warum schreit er?\nA: Er hat 'Ruhezeit!' geschrien.\nB: Er hat recht, auch wenn er schreit.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbor is screaming!\nB: Why is he screaming?\nA: He screamed 'Quiet hours!'\nB: He's right, even if he's screaming.",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: schrie, geschrien. From the same root as English 'shriek.' 'Schrei nicht so!' is neighbor-dispute standard vocabulary."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"schweigen",src:"[AR] to be silent, to stay quiet",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: schwieg, geschwiegen. The opposite of schreien.\nSchweigen ist Gold = Silence is golden.",example:"A: Was hat der Nachbar gesagt?\nB: Nichts. Er schweigt seit gestern.\nA: Er schweigt? Kein Wort?\nB: Kein Wort. Nur Schweigen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: What did the neighbor say?\nB: Nothing. He has been silent since yesterday.\nA: He's silent? Not a word?\nB: Not a word. Just silence.",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: schwieg, geschwiegen. The opposite of schreien. 'Schweigen ist Gold' (Silence is golden). A verb that means NOT making sound. Very German."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"klagen",src:"[AR] to complain, to sue",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Same word for both meanings.\nÜber etwas klagen = to complain about.\nGegen jemanden klagen = to sue someone.",example:"A: Der Nachbar klagt über den Lärm.\nB: Klagt er nur, oder klagt er vor Gericht?\nA: Erstmal klagt er nur.\nB: Hoffentlich bleibt es dabei.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbor is complaining about the noise.\nB: Is he just complaining, or is he suing?\nA: Just complaining for now.\nB: Hopefully it stays that way.",funFact:"[AR] Same word for both complaining and suing. In Germany, complaining and suing share linguistic DNA. The preposition decides: 'über' for complaining, 'gegen' for suing."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"streiken",src:"[AR] to go on strike",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] From English 'strike.' Borrowed during the Industrial Revolution.\nDeutsche Bahn strikes are legendary.",example:"A: Die Müllabfuhr streikt.\nB: Seit wann streiken sie?\nA: Seit drei Tagen.\nB: Kein Wunder, dass es hier stinkt.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The garbage collectors are on strike.\nB: Since when have they been striking?\nA: For three days.\nB: No wonder it stinks here.",funFact:"[AR] From English 'strike.' Germans borrowed it during the Industrial Revolution. Deutsche Bahn strikes are legendary. 'Die Nachbarn streiken' could mean they are on a noise protest."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"bloß",src:"[AR] just, merely, only",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"[AR] As a Modalpartikel, adds desperation or emphasis.\nWas soll ich bloß tun? = What on earth should I do?",example:"A: Was soll ich bloß tun?\nB: Dich entschuldigen.\nA: Bloß das?\nB: Ja, bloß das. Ein einfaches 'Entschuldigung' reicht.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: What on earth should I do?\nB: Apologize.\nA: Just that?\nB: Yes, just that. A simple 'sorry' is enough.",funFact:"[AR] As a Modalpartikel, it adds desperation or emphasis. 'Was soll ich bloß tun?' expresses helplessness. Verumius is thinking this right now."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"tense",art:"de-ber-apartment-door",trg:"Nachdem Verumius die Bohrmaschine abgestellt hatte, klopfte es an der Tür.",src:"[AR] After Verumius had turned off the drill, there was a knock at the door."},
        {type:"mc",q:"Der Nachbar steht in der Tür, rot im Gesicht, und schreit wegen des Lärms. Welches Wort beschreibt sein Gefühl gerade?",opts:["still","ernst","bloß","wütend"],ans:"wütend",hint:"[AR] This word comes from 'Wut' (rage) and means full of anger."}
      ]},
    {id:"deu_r16l2",title:"Die Hausordnung",icon:"📋",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Die Hausordnung",desc:"[AR] Every German apartment building has a Hausordnung (house rules). Today you learn the language of blame, criticism, and compromise.",goals:[
            "[AR] Learn vocabulary for arguments, complaints, and conflict resolution",
            "[AR] Master words for blame, criticism, and compromise",
            "[AR] Understand how Germans express disagreements"
          ]},
        {type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"foreboding",art:"de-ber-apartment-note",trg:"Unter der Tür lag ein Zettel. Handgeschrieben, in Großbuchstaben: 'SONNTAG. RUHEZEIT. PARAGRAPH 3. IHR NACHBAR.'",src:"[AR] Under the door lay a note. Handwritten, in capital letters: 'SUNDAY. QUIET HOURS. PARAGRAPH 3. YOUR NEIGHBOR.'"},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Schuld",src:"[AR] the guilt, the fault, the debt",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Three meanings in one word. Wer hat Schuld? = Whose fault?\nEntschuldigung literally means 'un-guilting.'",example:"A: Wer hat Schuld an dem Streit?\nB: Beide Seiten haben Schuld.\nA: Verumius hat die Ruhezeit verletzt.\nB: Aber der Nachbar hat geschrien.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Who is at fault for the argument?\nB: Both sides are at fault.\nA: Verumius violated the quiet hours.\nB: But the neighbor screamed.",funFact:"[AR] Three meanings in one word: guilt, fault, debt. 'Schulden' (debts) is the plural. 'Entschuldigung' literally means 'un-guilting.' You already know that word from Unit 1."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"schuldig",src:"[AR] guilty",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Er ist schuldig = He is guilty. Used in courtrooms and arguments.\nThe opposite: unschuldig = innocent.",example:"A: Ist er schuldig?\nB: Der Richter sagt: schuldig.\nA: Und der Nachbar?\nB: Auch nicht ganz unschuldig.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Is he guilty?\nB: The judge says: guilty.\nA: And the neighbor?\nB: Also not entirely innocent.",funFact:"[AR] The -ig ending turns the noun Schuld into an adjective. Used in courtrooms and arguments. The opposite: unschuldig (innocent)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"schuld",src:"[AR] at fault (predicative only)",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Er ist schuld = He is to blame. Only with 'sein.'\nNo endings, no declension. A stripped-down blame word.",example:"A: Wer ist schuld?\nB: Verumius ist schuld.\nA: Nur er?\nB: Na ja, beide sind ein bisschen schuld.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Who is to blame?\nB: Verumius is to blame.\nA: Only him?\nB: Well, both are a little to blame.",funFact:"[AR] Unlike 'schuldig,' this form is only used with 'sein.' No endings, no declension. A stripped-down blame word for everyday finger-pointing."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Kritik",src:"[AR] the criticism",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] From Greek 'kritike' (the art of judging).\nKritik üben = to exercise criticism (formal phrase).",example:"A: Die Kritik des Nachbarn war hart.\nB: Aber konstruktive Kritik?\nA: Nein, nur Beschwerden.\nB: Das ist keine Kritik, das ist Meckern.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbor's criticism was harsh.\nB: But constructive criticism?\nA: No, just complaints.\nB: That's not criticism, that's grumbling.",funFact:"[AR] From Greek 'kritike' (the art of judging). Germans value 'konstruktive Kritik' (constructive criticism) in the workplace. Destructive criticism is just Meckern (grumbling)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Respekt",src:"[AR] the respect",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] Same in English, French, and many other languages.\nRespekt haben vor = to have respect for.",example:"A: Man muss Respekt vor den Nachbarn haben.\nB: Respekt bedeutet: leise sein nach acht.\nA: Stimmt. Respekt ist keine Einbahnstraße.\nB: Respekt!",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: You must have respect for the neighbors.\nB: Respect means: be quiet after eight.\nA: True. Respect is not a one-way street.\nB: Respect!",funFact:"[AR] Same word in English, French, and a dozen other languages. 'Respekt!' on its own is slang for 'impressive!' Used seriously and casually."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Geduld",src:"[AR] the patience",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] From 'dulden' (to endure). Geduld ist eine Tugend = Patience is a virtue.\nThe opposite: Ungeduld = impatience.",example:"A: Ich brauche Geduld mit meinem Nachbarn.\nB: Geduld ist eine Tugend.\nA: Wie lange muss ich noch Geduld haben?\nB: Bis er dir verzeiht.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: I need patience with my neighbor.\nB: Patience is a virtue.\nA: How long do I still need to be patient?\nB: Until he forgives you.",funFact:"[AR] From 'dulden' (to endure). German bureaucracy requires enormous Geduld. The opposite is Ungeduld. 'Geduld ist eine Tugend' mirrors 'patience is a virtue.'"},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Kompromiss",src:"[AR] the compromise",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] From Latin 'compromissum.' In apartment disputes, the Kompromiss is king.\nEinen Kompromiss finden = to find a compromise.",example:"A: Wir müssen einen Kompromiss finden.\nB: Welchen Kompromiss?\nA: Du bohrst nicht am Sonntag, ich beschwere mich nicht mehr.\nB: Das klingt nach einem fairen Kompromiss.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: We need to find a compromise.\nB: What compromise?\nA: You don't drill on Sunday, I stop complaining.\nB: That sounds like a fair compromise.",funFact:"[AR] From Latin 'compromissum.' In German apartment disputes, the Kompromiss is king. 'Einen Kompromiss finden' resolves most Streit situations."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"nervous",art:"de-ber-apartment-hausordnung",trg:"Ich habe die Hausordnung gelesen. Zum ersten Mal. Paragraph drei war unterstrichen. Nicht von mir.",src:"[AR] I read the Hausordnung. For the first time. Paragraph three was underlined. Not by me."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"das Verständnis",src:"[AR] the understanding, the comprehension",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"[AR] From 'verstehen' (to understand). The -nis ending creates neuter abstract nouns.\nIch habe Verständnis dafür = I understand/sympathize.",example:"A: Ich habe Verständnis für den Nachbarn.\nB: Wirklich?\nA: Ja, er braucht seine Ruhe.\nB: Dann zeig ihm dein Verständnis.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: I have understanding for the neighbor.\nB: Really?\nA: Yes, he needs his peace.\nB: Then show him your understanding.",funFact:"[AR] The -nis ending creates neuter abstract nouns: Ergebnis, Erlebnis, Verständnis. From 'verstehen' (to understand). A word for empathy with a grammatical pattern."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Stimme",src:"[AR] the voice, the vote",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Also means 'vote' (die Stimme abgeben = to cast a vote).\nFrom 'stimmen' (to be correct / to tune).",example:"A: Ich höre eine laute Stimme.\nB: Das ist der Nachbar. Er hat eine starke Stimme.\nA: Er erhebt seine Stimme.\nB: Ja, und seine Stimme klingt wütend.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: I hear a loud voice.\nB: That's the neighbor. He has a strong voice.\nA: He is raising his voice.\nB: Yes, and his voice sounds angry.",funFact:"[AR] Also means 'vote' (die Stimme abgeben = to cast a vote). From 'stimmen' (to be correct/to tune). Your voice, your vote, your tuning fork. All one word."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Gedanke",src:"[AR] the thought",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] From 'denken' (to think). Weak masculine noun (N-Deklination):\nden Gedanken, dem Gedanken.",example:"A: Was ist dein erster Gedanke?\nB: Mein erster Gedanke: Entschuldigung.\nA: Ein guter Gedanke.\nB: Ja, jetzt muss ich diesen Gedanken umsetzen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: What is your first thought?\nB: My first thought: apology.\nA: A good thought.\nB: Yes, now I need to act on this thought.",funFact:"[AR] From 'denken' (to think). Weak masculine noun: der Gedanke, den Gedanken, dem Gedanken. One of those N-Deklination words."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"kritisieren",src:"[AR] to criticize",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] From Kritik. The -ieren ending marks verbs borrowed from French/Latin.\nAlways regular, always stressed on -ier-.",example:"A: Der Nachbar kritisiert mich ständig.\nB: Was genau kritisiert er?\nA: Alles. Den Lärm, die Musik, sogar meinen Müll.\nB: Manche Leute kritisieren einfach gern.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbor criticizes me constantly.\nB: What exactly does he criticize?\nA: Everything. The noise, the music, even my trash.\nB: Some people just like to criticize.",funFact:"[AR] The -ieren ending marks verbs borrowed from French or Latin. Always regular, always stressed on the -ier-. 'Alles kritisieren' is a German stereotype."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"beleidigen",src:"[AR] to insult, to offend",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Beleidigung (insult) is a crime in German law (Section 185 StGB).\nYou can be fined for insulting someone.",example:"A: Hat der Nachbar dich beleidigt?\nB: Ja, er hat mich beleidigt.\nA: Was hat er gesagt?\nB: Er hat mich einen 'rücksichtslosen Bohrer' genannt.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Did the neighbor insult you?\nB: Yes, he insulted me.\nA: What did he say?\nB: He called me a 'inconsiderate driller.'",funFact:"[AR] 'Beleidigung' (insult) is actually a crime in German law (Section 185 StGB). You can be fined for insulting someone. The German legal system takes words seriously."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"neighbor",mood:"cold",art:"de-ber-stairwell-confrontation",trg:"Verumius traf den Nachbarn im Treppenhaus. Der Nachbar sagte kein Wort. Er zeigte nur auf die Wand, wo sein Zettel hing. Dann ging er weiter.",src:"[AR] Verumius met the neighbor in the stairwell. The neighbor said nothing. He just pointed at the wall where his note hung. Then he walked on."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"unterbrechen",src:"[AR] to interrupt",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Unter (under) + brechen (break). You break into someone's speech.\nInseparable prefix: Er unterbricht mich ständig.",example:"A: Lass mich ausreden! Du unterbrichst mich!\nB: Entschuldigung, ich unterbreche dich nicht mehr.\nA: Danke. Also, ich wollte sagen...\nB: Ja? Was?",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Let me finish! You're interrupting me!\nB: Sorry, I won't interrupt you anymore.\nA: Thanks. So, I wanted to say...\nB: Yes? What?",funFact:"[AR] Unter (under) + brechen (break). You break into someone's speech from below. Inseparable prefix: 'Er unterbricht mich ständig.' A polite-sounding word for rude behavior."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"widersprechen",src:"[AR] to contradict",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Wider (against) + sprechen (speak). To speak against.\nInseparable. Takes dative: Ich widerspreche dir.",example:"A: Ich widerspreche dir.\nB: Warum widersprichst du mir?\nA: Weil du nicht recht hast.\nB: Jeder hat das Recht zu widersprechen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: I contradict you.\nB: Why are you contradicting me?\nA: Because you are not right.\nB: Everyone has the right to contradict.",funFact:"[AR] Wider (against) + sprechen (speak). To speak against. Takes dative. A polite argument verb. 'Ich muss Ihnen widersprechen' is formal disagreement."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"verlangen",src:"[AR] to demand, to require",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Stronger than 'bitten' (to ask).\n'Das ist zu viel verlangt' means 'That is asking too much.'",example:"A: Der Nachbar verlangt eine Entschuldigung.\nB: Er verlangt das?\nA: Ja, er verlangt sogar eine schriftliche.\nB: Das ist zu viel verlangt!",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbor demands an apology.\nB: He demands that?\nA: Yes, he even demands a written one.\nB: That is asking too much!",funFact:"[AR] Stronger than 'bitten' (to ask). When your neighbor verlangt something, the Streit is escalating. 'Das ist zu viel verlangt' is a useful pushback phrase."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"behaupten",src:"[AR] to claim, to assert",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'Haupt' (head). To hold your head up, maintain a position.\nEr behauptet, dass... = He claims that...",example:"A: Der Nachbar behauptet, dass ich jeden Tag bohre.\nB: Stimmt das?\nA: Nein! Ich behaupte das Gegenteil.\nB: Wer behauptet was, ist die Frage.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbor claims that I drill every day.\nB: Is that true?\nA: No! I claim the opposite.\nB: Who claims what is the question.",funFact:"[AR] From 'Haupt' (head). To hold your head up, to maintain a position. Essential for indirect speech and reported claims. 'Er behauptet, dass...' is how arguments escalate."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"frech",src:"[AR] cheeky, rude",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Sei nicht so frech! = Don't be so rude!\nOriginally meant 'brave/bold' in Old High German.",example:"A: Der Nachbar war ziemlich frech.\nB: Was hat er gesagt?\nA: 'Gehen Sie zurück in Ihr Land!'\nB: Das ist nicht frech, das ist beleidigend.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbor was quite rude.\nB: What did he say?\nA: 'Go back to your country!'\nB: That's not rude, that's offensive.",funFact:"[AR] Originally meant 'brave/bold' in Old High German. The meaning shifted from courage to impudence over centuries. 'Sei nicht so frech!' is every German parent's battle cry."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"peinlich",src:"[AR] embarrassing",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'Pein' (pain/torment). Something peinlich causes social pain.\n'Das ist mir peinlich' means 'That embarrasses me.'",example:"A: Die Situation war sehr peinlich.\nB: Was war peinlich?\nA: Alle Nachbarn haben den Streit gehört.\nB: Das ist wirklich peinlich.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The situation was very embarrassing.\nB: What was embarrassing?\nA: All the neighbors heard the argument.\nB: That is really embarrassing.",funFact:"[AR] From 'Pein' (pain/torment). Something peinlich causes social pain. 'Das ist mir peinlich.' Drilling on a Sunday? Peinlich."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"merkwürdig",src:"[AR] strange, odd",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Literally 'worthy of noticing' (merken + würdig).\nOriginally positive: remarkable. Now mostly means weird.",example:"A: Das ist merkwürdig.\nB: Was ist merkwürdig?\nA: Der Nachbar hat plötzlich aufgehört zu klopfen.\nB: Vielleicht ist er eingeschlafen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: That is strange.\nB: What is strange?\nA: The neighbor suddenly stopped knocking.\nB: Maybe he fell asleep.",funFact:"[AR] Literally 'worthy of noticing' (merken + würdig). Originally positive: remarkable. Now mostly means weird. The shift from 'noteworthy' to 'odd' happened over centuries."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"seltsam",src:"[AR] strange, peculiar",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'selten' (rarely). Something that happens seldom is seltsam.\nSlightly softer than merkwürdig.",example:"A: Ein seltsamer Nachbar.\nB: Warum seltsam?\nA: Er schreibt Zettel statt zu reden.\nB: Das ist nicht seltsam, das ist deutsch.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: A peculiar neighbor.\nB: Why peculiar?\nA: He writes notes instead of talking.\nB: That's not peculiar, that's German.",funFact:"[AR] From 'selten' (rarely). Something that happens seldom is seltsam. Slightly softer than merkwürdig. 'Ein seltsamer Nachbar' is the polite way to say 'a weird neighbor.'"},
        {type:"mc",q:"Der Nachbar sagt, es ist Verumius' Fehler. Welcher Satz passt?",opts:["Er hat Respekt.","Er ist still.","Er ist schuld.","Er hat Geduld."],ans:"Er ist schuld.",hint:"[AR] The predicative adjective meaning 'to be at fault.' Which verb links the subject to this state?"},
        {type:"fb",s:"Der Nachbar {1}, dass Verumius zu laut war.",a:["behauptet"],opts:["behauptet","kritisiert","beleidigt","unterbricht"],hint:"[AR] Which verb means to claim or to make an assertion?",sSrc:"[AR] The neighbor claims that Verumius was too loud."},
        {type:"match",pairs:[
            {trg:"Kritik",src:"criticism"},
            {trg:"Kompromiss",src:"compromise"},
            {trg:"Vorwurf",src:"accusation"},
            {trg:"Geduld",src:"patience"},
            {trg:"Schuld",src:"guilt/fault"},
            {trg:"Verständnis",src:"understanding"}
          ]},
        {type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"ominous",art:"de-ber-stairwell-notes",trg:"Verumius ging schlafen. Um 6:47 Uhr fand er den zweiten Zettel. Diesmal nicht unter der Tür. An der Wand im Treppenhaus. Für alle sichtbar.",src:"[AR] Verumius went to sleep. At 6:47 AM he found the second note. This time not under the door. On the wall in the stairwell. Visible to everyone."}
      ]},
    {id:"deu_r16l3",title:"Die Zettel an der Wand",icon:"📌",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Die Zettel an der Wand",desc:"[AR] The next morning, three new notes hang in the stairwell. The conflict escalates on paper. Time to learn mediation vocabulary and master 'nachdem + Plusquamperfekt.'",goals:[
            "[AR] Learn vocabulary for mediation and conflict resolution",
            "[AR] Master 'nachdem + Plusquamperfekt' for time sequences",
            "[AR] Read the note war in the stairwell"
          ]},
        {type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"humorous",art:"de-ber-stairwell-notes",trg:"Nachdem Verumius den ersten Zettel gelesen hatte, fand er am nächsten Morgen drei neue Zettel an der Wand.",src:"[AR] After Verumius had read the first note, he found three new notes on the wall the next morning."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"das Geheimnis",src:"[AR] the secret",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"[AR] From 'geheim' (secret). The -nis ending creates neuter nouns.\nEin offenes Geheimnis = an open secret.",example:"A: Das Treppenhaus hat ein Geheimnis.\nB: Was für ein Geheimnis?\nA: Jeder weiß, wer die Zettel schreibt.\nB: Das ist ein offenes Geheimnis.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The stairwell has a secret.\nB: What kind of secret?\nA: Everyone knows who writes the notes.\nB: That's an open secret.",funFact:"[AR] From 'geheim' (secret). The -nis ending creates neuter nouns. 'Ein offenes Geheimnis' is one everyone knows but nobody says aloud."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"das Gewissen",src:"[AR] the conscience",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"[AR] From 'wissen' (to know). Your Gewissen is what you know inside.\nEin schlechtes Gewissen haben = to have a guilty conscience.",example:"A: Hast du ein schlechtes Gewissen?\nB: Ja, mein Gewissen plagt mich.\nA: Dann entschuldige dich.\nB: Mein Gewissen sagt das Gleiche.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Do you have a guilty conscience?\nB: Yes, my conscience is plaguing me.\nA: Then apologize.\nB: My conscience says the same thing.",funFact:"[AR] From 'wissen' (to know). Your Gewissen is what you know inside. 'Ein gutes Gewissen ist ein sanftes Ruhekissen' (A good conscience is a soft pillow)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Herausforderung",src:"[AR] the challenge",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Heraus (out) + Forderung (demand). 16 letters.\nA demand that pulls you out of comfort.",example:"A: Das Zusammenleben ist eine Herausforderung.\nB: Ja, eine große Herausforderung.\nA: Aber jede Herausforderung macht stärker.\nB: Philosophisch. Aber wahr.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Living together is a challenge.\nB: Yes, a big challenge.\nA: But every challenge makes you stronger.\nB: Philosophical. But true.",funFact:"[AR] Heraus (out) + Forderung (demand). A demand that pulls you out of comfort. 16 letters. Living in Germany as a foreigner is eine große Herausforderung."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Kraft",src:"[AR] the strength, the power, the force",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Mit voller Kraft = with full force.\nKraftwerk = power plant (and the famous electronic band).",example:"A: Ich brauche Kraft für dieses Gespräch.\nB: Du hast die Kraft.\nA: Woher nimmst du die Kraft?\nB: Aus dem Kaffee. Immer aus dem Kaffee.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: I need strength for this conversation.\nB: You have the strength.\nA: Where do you get the strength from?\nB: From the coffee. Always from the coffee.",funFact:"[AR] 'Mit voller Kraft' (with full force). Also in compound: 'Kraftwerk' (power plant, and the famous electronic band). Die Kraft is feminine, like most abstract -ft nouns."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Mut",src:"[AR] the courage",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] Mut machen = to encourage. Mutig = courageous.\nVerumius braucht Mut, um an die Tür zu klopfen.",example:"A: Hast du den Mut, zum Nachbarn zu gehen?\nB: Ich brauche noch etwas Mut.\nA: Mut ist, wenn man Angst hat und es trotzdem tut.\nB: Okay. Ich gehe.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Do you have the courage to go to the neighbor?\nB: I need a bit more courage.\nA: Courage is when you're scared and do it anyway.\nB: Okay. I'll go.",funFact:"[AR] 'Mut machen' (to encourage). 'Mutig' (courageous). Verumius needs Mut to knock on the neighbor's door and apologize."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"das Herz",src:"القلب",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"[AR] Same root as English 'heart,' Latin 'cor,' Greek 'kardia.'\nVon Herzen = from the heart. Herzlich = heartfelt.",example:"A: Sprich von Herzen.\nB: Mein Herz sagt: Entschuldigung.\nA: Dann sag es mit Herz.\nB: Okay. Von ganzem Herzen: Es tut mir leid.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Speak from the heart.\nB: My heart says: sorry.\nA: Then say it with heart.\nB: Okay. With all my heart: I'm sorry.",funFact:"[AR] Same root as English 'heart,' Latin 'cor,' Greek 'kardia.' 'Von Herzen' (from the heart). 'Herzlich' (heartfelt) you already know from Unit 1."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"das Gefühl",src:"[AR] the feeling, the emotion",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"[AR] From 'fühlen' (to feel). Plural: Gefühle.\nThe Ge- prefix + -l ending creates neuter collective nouns.",example:"A: Was ist dein Gefühl bei der Sache?\nB: Mein Gefühl sagt: entschuldigen.\nA: Vertrau deinem Gefühl.\nB: Meine Gefühle sind gemischt.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: What is your feeling about the matter?\nB: My feeling says: apologize.\nA: Trust your feeling.\nB: My feelings are mixed.",funFact:"[AR] From 'fühlen' (to feel). The Ge- prefix + -l ending creates neuter collective nouns. 'Ein gutes Gefühl haben' means to have a good feeling about something."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"beruhigen",src:"[AR] to calm (someone) down",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Be- + ruhig (quiet) + -en. Reflexive: sich beruhigen.\nThe be- prefix makes it transitive: you calm SOMEONE.",example:"A: Beruhige dich!\nB: Ich kann mich nicht beruhigen.\nA: Trink einen Tee. Das beruhigt.\nB: Okay, ich versuche mich zu beruhigen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Calm down!\nB: I can't calm down.\nA: Drink a tea. That calms.\nB: Okay, I'll try to calm down.",funFact:"[AR] Be- + ruhig (quiet) + -en. 'Beruhige dich!' (Calm down!). The be- prefix makes it transitive: you calm SOMEONE. Reflexive: 'sich beruhigen.'"},
        {type:"teach",trg:"entspannen",src:"[AR] to relax",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Ent- (un-) + spannen (to tense). To un-tense.\nEntspann dich! = Relax! Entspannung = relaxation.",example:"A: Du musst dich entspannen.\nB: Wie soll ich mich entspannen?\nA: Yoga? Meditation?\nB: Ich entspanne mich mit einer Bohrmaschine. Oh, warte...",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: You need to relax.\nB: How should I relax?\nA: Yoga? Meditation?\nB: I relax with a drill. Oh, wait...",funFact:"[AR] Ent- (un-) + spannen (to tense). To un-tense. 'Entspann dich!' (Relax!). 'Entspannung' (relaxation) is a German wellness keyword."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"einigen",src:"[AR] to agree, to unite",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Sich einigen = to reach agreement. From 'ein' (one).\nWir haben uns geeinigt = We reached an agreement.",example:"A: Können wir uns einigen?\nB: Ich hoffe, wir einigen uns.\nA: Worüber sollen wir uns einigen?\nB: Über die Ruhezeiten.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Can we reach an agreement?\nB: I hope we agree.\nA: What should we agree on?\nB: On the quiet hours.",funFact:"[AR] From 'ein' (one). To become one mind. 'Wir haben uns geeinigt' (We reached an agreement). Essential conflict resolution verb."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"entgegenkommen",src:"[AR] to meet halfway, to accommodate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Entgegen (toward) + kommen (come). Separable.\nEr kommt mir entgegen = He meets me halfway.",example:"A: Der Nachbar kommt mir entgegen.\nB: Wirklich? Wie kommt er dir entgegen?\nA: Er erlaubt Bohren bis 19 Uhr.\nB: Das ist nett. Komm ihm auch entgegen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbor is meeting me halfway.\nB: Really? How is he meeting you halfway?\nA: He allows drilling until 7 PM.\nB: That's nice. Meet him halfway too.",funFact:"[AR] Entgegen (toward) + kommen (come). Separable: 'Er kommt mir entgegen.' Literally: someone comes toward you. Figuratively: compromise."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"überzeugen",src:"[AR] to convince",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Über (over) + zeugen (to witness/testify). Inseparable.\nIch bin überzeugt = I am convinced.",example:"A: Kannst du den Nachbarn überzeugen?\nB: Ich versuche ihn zu überzeugen.\nA: Bist du überzeugt, dass es klappt?\nB: Ich bin nicht überzeugt, aber ich versuche es.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Can you convince the neighbor?\nB: I'll try to convince him.\nA: Are you convinced it will work?\nB: I'm not convinced, but I'll try.",funFact:"[AR] Über (over) + zeugen (to witness/testify). To bring someone over to your testimony. 'Ich bin überzeugt' (I am convinced). Inseparable prefix."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"überreden",src:"[AR] to persuade, to talk into",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Über + reden (talk). Slightly manipulative vs überzeugen.\n'Er hat mich überredet' means 'He talked me into it.'",example:"A: Hildi hat mich überredet.\nB: Wozu hat sie dich überredet?\nA: Zum Nachbarn zu gehen und mich zu entschuldigen.\nB: Überredet oder überzeugt?",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Hildi talked me into it.\nB: Into what did she talk you?\nA: Going to the neighbor and apologizing.\nB: Talked into or convinced?",funFact:"[AR] Über + reden (talk). To talk someone over. Slightly manipulative compared to überzeugen. 'Überreden' uses emotion; 'überzeugen' uses logic."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"loben",src:"[AR] to praise",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Lob = praise (noun). Nicht geschimpft ist genug gelobt.\nGermans praise sparingly; when they loben, they mean it.",example:"A: Hildi lobt Verumius.\nB: Wofür lobt sie ihn?\nA: Für seinen Mut.\nB: Ein Lob von Hildi ist viel wert.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Hildi praises Verumius.\nB: What does she praise him for?\nA: For his courage.\nB: A compliment from Hildi is worth a lot.",funFact:"[AR] 'Nicht geschimpft ist genug gelobt' (Not scolded is enough praised) is a Swabian saying. Germans praise sparingly; when they loben, they mean it."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"hildi",mood:"amused",art:"de-ber-stairwell-calligraphy",trg:"Hildi schrieb ihren eigenen Zettel. In Schönschrift. Mit Tinte. Er lautete: 'Liebe Hausbewohner, bitte beachten Sie, dass passive Aggression auch nach 20 Uhr verboten sein sollte.'",src:"[AR] Hildi wrote her own note. In calligraphy. With ink. It read: 'Dear residents, please note that passive aggression should also be prohibited after 8 PM.'"},
        {type:"teach",trg:"reichen",src:"[AR] to suffice, to hand/pass",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Two meanings: 'Das reicht!' (That is enough!) and\n'Kannst du mir das Salz reichen?' (Can you pass me the salt?).",example:"A: Reicht eine Entschuldigung?\nB: Ich glaube, das reicht.\nA: Kannst du mir den Zettel reichen?\nB: Hier, bitte. Reicht dir ein Zettel?",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Is an apology enough?\nB: I think that's enough.\nA: Can you pass me the note?\nB: Here you go. Is one note enough?",funFact:"[AR] Two everyday uses in one verb: 'Das reicht!' (That is enough!) and 'Kannst du mir das Salz reichen?' (Can you pass me the salt?). Context is everything."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"ehrlich",src:"[AR] honest",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'Ehre' (honor). Ehrlich gesagt... = Honestly speaking...\nEhrlich währt am längsten = Honesty lasts longest.",example:"A: Sei ehrlich. War es laut?\nB: Ehrlich gesagt, ja.\nA: Danke für die ehrliche Antwort.\nB: Ehrlich währt am längsten.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Be honest. Was it loud?\nB: Honestly speaking, yes.\nA: Thanks for the honest answer.\nB: Honesty lasts longest.",funFact:"[AR] From 'Ehre' (honor). 'Ehrlich gesagt...' begins many German confessions. 'Ehrlich währt am längsten' is the German version of 'honesty is the best policy.'"},
        {type:"teach",trg:"fair",src:"[AR] fair",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Borrowed from English. Pronounced 'fehr' in German.\nAdopted because 'gerecht' felt too formal.",example:"A: Das war nicht fair!\nB: Was war nicht fair?\nA: Der Zettel an der Wand. Er nennt meinen Namen.\nB: Stimmt, das ist nicht fair.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: That was not fair!\nB: What was not fair?\nA: The note on the wall. It names my name.\nB: True, that is not fair.",funFact:"[AR] Borrowed from English. Pronounced 'fehr' in German. Used constantly in arguments. Germans adopted this word because 'gerecht' felt too formal for everyday disputes."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"tolerant",src:"[AR] tolerant",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Same spelling as English, from Latin 'tolerare' (to endure).\nBerlin prides itself on being tolerant.",example:"A: Man muss tolerant sein.\nB: Ich bin tolerant, aber nicht bei Lärm.\nA: Toleranz hat Grenzen?\nB: Jede Toleranz hat Grenzen. Besonders sonntags.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: You have to be tolerant.\nB: I'm tolerant, but not with noise.\nA: Tolerance has limits?\nB: Every tolerance has limits. Especially on Sundays.",funFact:"[AR] Same spelling as English, from Latin 'tolerare' (to endure). Berlin prides itself on being tolerant. The apartment building is testing that claim."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"treu",src:"[AR] loyal, faithful",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Treu wie Gold = faithful as gold. Same root as English 'true.'\nA treu friend, a treu dog, a treu neighbor.",example:"A: Ein treuer Nachbar beschwert sich nicht sofort.\nB: Bist du ein treuer Nachbar?\nA: Ich versuche treu zu sein.\nB: Dann sei treu und entschuldige dich.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: A loyal neighbor doesn't complain immediately.\nB: Are you a loyal neighbor?\nA: I try to be loyal.\nB: Then be loyal and apologize.",funFact:"[AR] Same root as English 'true.' 'Treu wie Gold' (faithful as gold). A treu friend, a treu dog, a treu neighbor who does not drill on Sundays."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"escalating",art:"de-ber-stairwell-notes-many",trg:"Am dritten Tag hingen sieben Zettel an der Wand. Drei vom Nachbarn. Zwei von Verumius. Einer von Hildi. Und einer von Frau Müller aus dem zweiten Stock: 'Könnten Sie ALLE leiser sein?'",src:"[AR] On the third day, seven notes hung on the wall. Three from the neighbor. Two from Verumius. One from Hildi. And one from Mrs. Müller on the second floor: 'Could you ALL be quieter?'"},
        {type:"teach",trg:"dankbar",src:"[AR] grateful",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Dank (thanks) + -bar (able). Ich bin dankbar = I am grateful.\nThe -bar suffix works like English '-able.'",example:"A: Ich bin dankbar für Hildis Hilfe.\nB: Wofür genau bist du dankbar?\nA: Dass sie zwischen uns vermittelt.\nB: Ja, wir sollten alle dankbar sein.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: I'm grateful for Hildi's help.\nB: What exactly are you grateful for?\nA: That she's mediating between us.\nB: Yes, we should all be grateful.",funFact:"[AR] Dank (thanks) + -bar (able). The -bar suffix works like English '-able': dankbar, machbar (doable), essbar (edible)."},
        {type:"tip",title:"nachdem + Plusquamperfekt: Ordering Past Events",text:"[AR] 'nachdem' = 'after.' The nachdem clause uses the Plusquamperfekt (hatte/war + Partizip II) because the event happened FIRST.\n\nThe main clause uses Perfekt or Präteritum.\n\nExample:\nNachdem er den Zettel gelesen hatte, ging er zum Nachbarn.\n(After he had read the note, he went to the neighbor.)\n\nThe verb goes to the END in the nachdem clause.\n\nEarlier (Plusquamperfekt) -> later (Präteritum/Perfekt).",deepDive:{title:"Plusquamperfekt: The Past Before the Past",text:"[AR] The Plusquamperfekt shows what happened BEFORE another event in the past.\n\nFormation: hatte/war + Partizip II\n\nWith haben: Ich hatte gelesen (I had read)\nWith sein: Er war gegangen (He had gone)\n\nNote: The same verbs that use 'sein' in Perfekt also use 'war' in Plusquamperfekt:\ngehen: war gegangen\nkommen: war gekommen\nfahren: war gefahren"}},
        {type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"overwhelmed",art:"de-ber-stairwell-notes-reading",trg:"Nachdem ich alle Zettel gelesen hatte, wusste ich eines sicher: Ich brauche Hilfe. Professionelle Hilfe. Ich brauche Hildi.",src:"[AR] After I had read all the notes, I knew one thing for certain: I need help. Professional help. I need Hildi."},
        {type:"fb",s:"Nachdem Verumius die Bohrmaschine abgestellt {1}, klopfte es an der Tür.",a:["hatte"],opts:["hatte","hat","war","ist"],hint:"[AR] The nachdem clause requires Plusquamperfekt. Which auxiliary verb goes with 'abgestellt'?",sSrc:"[AR] After Verumius had turned off the drill, there was a knock at the door."}
      ]},
    {id:"deu_r16l4",title:"Indirekte Fragen",icon:"❓",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Indirekte Fragen",desc:"[AR] Direct questions are direct. Indirect questions are polite. Learn how to ask elegantly in German without seeming rude.",goals:[
            "[AR] Master indirect questions with W-words and 'ob'",
            "[AR] Learn vocabulary for relationships and emotions",
            "[AR] Combine time sequences with indirect speech"
          ]},
        {type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"cautious",art:"de-ber-stairwell-reading",trg:"Hildi sagte: 'Frag nicht direkt. Frag höflich.' Ich fragte mich, ob man mit indirekten Fragen auch indirekte Nachbarn beschwichtigen kann.",src:"[AR] Hildi said: 'Don't ask directly. Ask politely.' I wondered whether you can appease indirect neighbors with indirect questions."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Diskussion",src:"[AR] the discussion",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] From Latin 'discussio' (examination). More structured than a Streit.\nEine Diskussion führen = to lead a discussion.",example:"A: Wir brauchen eine sachliche Diskussion.\nB: Keine Diskussion ohne Respekt.\nA: Die Diskussion über Lärm muss sein.\nB: Einverstanden. Beginnen wir die Diskussion.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: We need an objective discussion.\nB: No discussion without respect.\nA: The discussion about noise must happen.\nB: Agreed. Let's begin the discussion.",funFact:"[AR] From Latin 'discussio' (examination). More structured than a Streit. Germans value 'sachliche Diskussion' (objective discussion). Subjective = Streit. Objective = Diskussion."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Beziehung",src:"[AR] the relationship",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] From 'beziehen' (to relate to). Covers romantic, professional, international.\nIn einer Beziehung sein = to be in a relationship.",example:"A: Wie ist deine Beziehung zum Nachbarn?\nB: Kompliziert. Die Beziehung ist angespannt.\nA: Eine gute Beziehung braucht Arbeit.\nB: Wie bei jeder Beziehung.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: How is your relationship with the neighbor?\nB: Complicated. The relationship is tense.\nA: A good relationship takes work.\nB: Like every relationship.",funFact:"[AR] From 'beziehen' (to relate to). Covers romantic, professional, and international relationships. 'In einer Beziehung sein' is the Facebook status in German."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Freundschaft",src:"[AR] the friendship",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Freund + -schaft (collective suffix, like English '-ship').\nGermans distinguish sharply between Freunde and Bekannte.",example:"A: Kann aus Nachbarschaft Freundschaft werden?\nB: Manchmal. Echte Freundschaft braucht Zeit.\nA: Freundschaft beginnt mit Respekt.\nB: Und Marmelade.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Can neighborhood turn into friendship?\nB: Sometimes. Real friendship takes time.\nA: Friendship begins with respect.\nB: And jam.",funFact:"[AR] Freund (friend) + -schaft (collective suffix, like English '-ship'). Germans distinguish sharply between Freunde (friends) and Bekannte (acquaintances). Freundschaft is earned, not given."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Ehe",src:"[AR] the marriage",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] One of the shortest German nouns. From Old High German 'ewa' (law).\nDie Ehe schließen = to enter marriage.",example:"A: Eine Ehe ist wie eine Nachbarschaft.\nB: Wie meinst du das?\nA: Man muss Kompromisse finden.\nB: In der Ehe und im Treppenhaus.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: A marriage is like a neighborhood.\nB: What do you mean?\nA: You have to find compromises.\nB: In marriage and in the stairwell.",funFact:"[AR] One of the shortest German nouns. From Old High German 'ewa' (law/eternity). 'Ehe' also means 'before' as a conjunction. Marriage and 'before' share a word. Coincidence? Debatable."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"das Ehepaar",src:"[AR] the married couple",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"[AR] Ehe + Paar (pair). The compound tells you everything:\na pair bonded by Ehe.",example:"A: Das Ehepaar von nebenan ist nett.\nB: Welches Ehepaar?\nA: Herr und Frau Müller.\nB: Ach, das Ehepaar mit dem Hund.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The married couple next door is nice.\nB: Which married couple?\nA: Mr. and Mrs. Müller.\nB: Oh, the married couple with the dog.",funFact:"[AR] Ehe + Paar (pair). The compound tells you everything: a pair bonded by Ehe. The neighbor and his wife are ein Ehepaar."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Scheidung",src:"[AR] the divorce",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] From 'scheiden' (to separate). Die Scheidung einreichen = to file for divorce.\nGermany has a mandatory one-year separation period.",example:"A: Die Scheidung war schwer.\nB: Ja, eine Scheidung ist nie leicht.\nA: Aber nach der Scheidung ging es besser.\nB: Manchmal ist eine Scheidung der richtige Weg.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The divorce was hard.\nB: Yes, a divorce is never easy.\nA: But after the divorce things got better.\nB: Sometimes a divorce is the right path.",funFact:"[AR] From 'scheiden' (to separate). Germany has a mandatory one-year separation period (Trennungsjahr) before divorce. No shortcuts."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Trennung",src:"[AR] the separation",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] From 'trennen' (to separate). Broader than Scheidung: any split.\nDie Trennung von Kirche und Staat = separation of church and state.",example:"A: Die Trennung vom Nachbarn wäre schön.\nB: Du kannst dich nicht von deinem Nachbarn trennen.\nA: Doch, ich ziehe um.\nB: Das ist eine radikale Trennung.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: A separation from the neighbor would be nice.\nB: You can't separate from your neighbor.\nA: Yes I can, I'll move.\nB: That's a radical separation.",funFact:"[AR] From 'trennen' (to separate). Broader than Scheidung: any split. 'Mulltrennung' (waste separation) uses the same word. Domestic and romantic contexts, same verb."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Schreck",src:"[AR] the fright, the shock",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] Einen Schreck bekommen = to get a fright.\nShort, sharp, immediate. The moment of shock.",example:"A: Ich habe einen Schreck bekommen!\nB: Warum? Was war der Schreck?\nA: Der Nachbar stand plötzlich vor der Tür.\nB: Das war ein großer Schreck.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: I got a fright!\nB: Why? What was the shock?\nA: The neighbor was suddenly at the door.\nB: That was a big fright.",funFact:"[AR] 'Einen Schreck bekommen' (to get a fright). Short, sharp, immediate. Der Schreck is the moment of shock. Related to 'erschrecken.'"},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Schrecken",src:"[AR] the horror, the terror",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] Longer and deeper than Schreck. Der Schrecken des Krieges = the horror of war.\nZu meinem Schrecken... = To my horror...",example:"A: Der Schrecken des Zettelkriegs.\nB: Schrecken? Das ist kein Krieg!\nA: Für Verumius ist es ein Schrecken.\nB: Zu meinem Schrecken hast du recht.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The horror of the note war.\nB: Horror? This is no war!\nA: For Verumius it is a horror.\nB: To my horror, you're right.",funFact:"[AR] Longer and deeper than Schreck. 'Der Schrecken des Krieges' (the horror of war). Can also mean fright: 'Zu meinem Schrecken...' (To my horror...)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Enttäuschung",src:"[AR] the disappointment",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Ent- (un-) + Täuschung (deception). To be un-deceived.\nGerman frames disappointment as losing a false belief.",example:"A: Was für eine Enttäuschung!\nB: Ja, die Enttäuschung ist groß.\nA: Ich bin enttäuscht vom Nachbarn.\nB: Jede Enttäuschung lehrt etwas.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: What a disappointment!\nB: Yes, the disappointment is great.\nA: I'm disappointed in the neighbor.\nB: Every disappointment teaches something.",funFact:"[AR] Ent- (un-) + Täuschung (deception). To be un-deceived, to have illusions removed. German frames disappointment as losing a false belief. Philosophical."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"leiden",src:"[AR] to suffer",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: litt, gelitten. 'Ich kann ihn nicht leiden' means 'I can't stand him.'\nAlso: Leid tun = to be sorry (Es tut mir leid).",example:"A: Ich leide unter dem Lärm.\nB: Ich kann den Lärm auch nicht leiden.\nA: Wir leiden beide.\nB: Ja, das ganze Haus leidet.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: I'm suffering from the noise.\nB: I can't stand the noise either.\nA: We're both suffering.\nB: Yes, the whole building is suffering.",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: litt, gelitten. 'Ich kann ihn nicht leiden' (I cannot stand him) is the common idiom. Also: 'Leid tun' (to be sorry). 'Es tut mir leid.'"},
        {type:"teach",trg:"enttäuschen",src:"[AR] to disappoint",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] From Enttäuschung. Inseparable prefix: ent- stays attached.\nDu enttäuschst mich = You disappoint me.",example:"A: Du enttäuschst mich.\nB: Es tut mir leid, dich zu enttäuschen.\nA: Enttäusch mich nicht noch einmal.\nB: Ich werde dich nicht enttäuschen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: You disappoint me.\nB: I'm sorry to disappoint you.\nA: Don't disappoint me again.\nB: I won't disappoint you.",funFact:"[AR] Inseparable prefix: ent- stays attached. Regular conjugation despite the irregular-looking stem. 'Du enttäuschst mich' is a heavy accusation in any language."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"erschrecken",src:"[AR] to frighten / to be frightened",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Two verbs in one! Transitive (frighten): regular.\nIntransitive (be frightened): irregular (erschrak, erschrocken).",example:"A: Erschreck mich nicht!\nB: Entschuldigung, ich wollte dich nicht erschrecken.\nA: Ich bin erschrocken.\nB: Ich erschrecke mich auch leicht.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Don't scare me!\nB: Sorry, I didn't mean to scare you.\nA: I was frightened.\nB: I also get scared easily.",funFact:"[AR] Two verbs in one. Transitive (frighten someone): regular. Intransitive (be frightened): irregular (erschrak, erschrocken). One of German's sneakiest verbs."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"observational",art:"de-ber-stairwell-notes-closeup",trg:"Im Treppenhaus hing jetzt ein neuer Zettel. In Schönschrift. Von Hildi. Er lautete: 'Könnten Sie mir bitte sagen, ob Sie auch nach 20 Uhr bohren müssen?'",src:"[AR] A new note now hung in the stairwell. In calligraphy. From Hildi. It read: 'Could you please tell me whether you also need to drill after 8 PM?'"},
        {type:"teach",trg:"trennen",src:"[AR] to separate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Sich trennen = to break up. Regular verb.\nMülltrennung = waste separation. Same verb, different contexts.",example:"A: Sollen wir uns trennen?\nB: Du meinst die Diskussion trennen?\nA: Ja, Thema Lärm und Thema Respekt trennen.\nB: Gute Idee. Eins nach dem anderen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Should we separate?\nB: You mean separate the discussion?\nA: Yes, separate the topic of noise and the topic of respect.\nB: Good idea. One at a time.",funFact:"[AR] 'Sich trennen' (to break up). Regular verb. 'Mülltrennung' (waste separation) was in U8. Same verb, domestic and romantic contexts."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"scheiden",src:"[AR] to divorce, to separate (formally)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: schied, geschieden. Sich scheiden lassen = to get divorced.\nThe 'lassen' construction adds formality.",example:"A: Sie wollen sich scheiden lassen.\nB: Warum lassen sie sich scheiden?\nA: Zu viel Streit.\nB: Nicht jeder Streit endet in Scheidung.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: They want to get divorced.\nB: Why are they getting divorced?\nA: Too much arguing.\nB: Not every argument ends in divorce.",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: schied, geschieden. 'Sich scheiden lassen' (to get divorced). The 'lassen' construction adds formality. Legal and permanent."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"fürchten",src:"[AR] to fear",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Sich fürchten vor = to be afraid of. From 'Furcht' (fear).\nFurchtbar = terrible (literally 'fear-able').",example:"A: Verumius fürchtet den nächsten Zettel.\nB: Er fürchtet sich vor dem Nachbarn?\nA: Nein, er fürchtet sich vor weiteren Beschwerden.\nB: Furcht ist normal nach einem Streit.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Verumius fears the next note.\nB: He's afraid of the neighbor?\nA: No, he's afraid of more complaints.\nB: Fear is normal after an argument.",funFact:"[AR] 'Sich fürchten vor' (to be afraid of). From 'Furcht' (fear). 'Furchtbar' (terrible, literally 'fear-able'). Verumius fürchtet sich vor dem nächsten Zettel."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"hassen",src:"[AR] to hate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Strong word. Regular conjugation. Same root as English 'hate.'\n'Hass' (hatred) is a legal concept in Hassrede (hate speech).",example:"A: Ich hasse Lärm.\nB: Alle hassen Lärm.\nA: Aber ich hasse auch Zettel.\nB: Du hasst Zettel mehr als Lärm?",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: I hate noise.\nB: Everyone hates noise.\nA: But I also hate notes.\nB: You hate notes more than noise?",funFact:"[AR] Strong word. Same root as English 'hate.' Germans use it seriously. 'Hass' (hatred) is also a legal concept in Hassrede (hate speech)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"langweilen",src:"[AR] to bore",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Sich langweilen = to be bored. From 'Langeweile' (boredom).\nReflexive for being bored, transitive for boring others.",example:"A: Langweilt dich der Streit?\nB: Nein, er langweilt mich nicht.\nA: Mich langweilt er schon.\nB: Dann lass uns den Streit beenden.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Does the argument bore you?\nB: No, it doesn't bore me.\nA: It bores me already.\nB: Then let's end the argument.",funFact:"[AR] 'Sich langweilen' (to be bored). From 'Langeweile' (boredom, literally 'long-while'). Reflexive for being bored, transitive for boring others."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"verzeihen",src:"[AR] to forgive",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: verzieh, verziehen. Verzeihung! = Forgiveness! (I'm sorry).\nMore formal than 'Entschuldigung.'",example:"A: Können Sie mir verzeihen?\nB: Ich verzeihe Ihnen.\nA: Wirklich? Sie verzeihen mir?\nB: Ja, Verzeihung gehört zum Leben.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Can you forgive me?\nB: I forgive you.\nA: Really? You forgive me?\nB: Yes, forgiveness is part of life.",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: verzieh, verziehen. 'Verzeihung!' is a formal apology, more polished than 'Entschuldigung.' The peace-offering verb."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"verzichten",src:"[AR] to give up, to do without",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Auf etwas verzichten = to forgo something.\nIch verzichte auf mein Recht = I waive my right.",example:"A: Ich verzichte auf das Bohren am Sonntag.\nB: Du verzichtest darauf? Wirklich?\nA: Ja, ich verzichte gern darauf.\nB: Darauf zu verzichten ist ein guter Anfang.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: I'm giving up drilling on Sundays.\nB: You're giving that up? Really?\nA: Yes, I'm happy to give it up.\nB: Giving that up is a good start.",funFact:"[AR] 'Auf etwas verzichten' (to forgo something). Takes auf + accusative. A conscious decision to let go. 'Ich verzichte auf mein Recht' (I waive my right)."},
        {type:"tip",title:"Indirect Questions: Polite German",text:"[AR] Direct: 'Wo ist das Büro?' (Where is the office?)\nIndirect: 'Können Sie mir sagen, wo das Büro ist?'\n\nThe verb moves to the END after the question word.\n\nFor yes/no questions use 'ob':\n'Wissen Sie, ob er zu Hause ist?' (Do you know whether he is home?)\n\nPolite introductions:\n- Können/Könnten Sie mir sagen, ...?\n- Ich möchte wissen, ...\n- Wissen Sie, ...?\n- Dürfte ich fragen, ...?",deepDive:{title:"Verb-Final Position in Subordinate Clauses",text:"[AR] In every subordinate clause, the conjugated verb goes to the END:\n\n- dass er kommt (that he comes)\n- weil sie krank ist (because she is sick)\n- ob er zu Hause ist (whether he is home)\n- wo das Büro ist (where the office is)\n\nIndirect questions are subordinate clauses, so the same rule applies: verb to the end.\n\nDirect: Wo ist er? -> Indirect: ..., wo er ist.\nDirect: Kommt er? -> Indirect: ..., ob er kommt."}},
        {type:"mc",q:"Verumius fragt höflich nach dem Weg zum Büro. Welcher Satz ist korrekt?",opts:[
            "Können Sie mir sagen, wo das Büro ist?",
            "Können Sie mir sagen, wo ist das Büro?",
            "Sagen Sie mir, wo ist das Büro?",
            "Wo das Büro ist, können Sie mir sagen?"
          ],ans:"Können Sie mir sagen, wo das Büro ist?",hint:"[AR] In indirect questions, the conjugated verb moves to the end of the clause."},
        {type:"drag_fill",s:"Nachdem er den Brief gelesen {1}, wollte er wissen, {2} der Nachbar wirklich wütend {3}.",blanks:{"1":"hatte","2":"ob","3":"war"},pool:["hatte","ob","war","hat","dass","ist"],hint:"[AR] A nachdem + Plusquamperfekt clause, followed by an indirect yes/no question with ob + verb at the end.",sSrc:"[AR] After he had read the letter, he wanted to know whether the neighbor was really angry."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"hopeful",art:"de-ber-stairwell-evening",trg:"Ich wollte wissen, ob der Nachbar mich versteht. Ob er mir verzeihen kann. Ob wir jemals wieder normal miteinander reden. Drei Fragen. Alle indirekt.",src:"[AR] I wanted to know whether the neighbor understands me. Whether he can forgive me. Whether we will ever talk normally again. Three questions. All indirect."}
      ]},
    {id:"deu_r16l5",title:"Hildi greift ein",icon:"⚖️",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Hildi greift ein",desc:"[AR] Hildi turns her living room into a courtroom. Tea, Hausordnung, and reading glasses. The mediation begins.",goals:[
            "[AR] Learn vocabulary for law and justice",
            "[AR] Practice nachdem and indirect questions in context",
            "[AR] Witness Hildi mediating better than any lawyer"
          ]},
        {type:"story",speaker:"hildi",mood:"authoritative",art:"de-ber-hildi-mediation",trg:"Nachdem ich die Hausordnung gelesen hatte, wusste ich sofort, wer Recht hat.",src:"[AR] After I had read the house rules, I knew immediately who is right."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Polizist",src:"[AR] the policeman",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] From 'Polizei' (police). Weak masculine noun (N-Deklination):\nden Polizisten, dem Polizisten.",example:"A: Sollen wir einen Polizisten rufen?\nB: Nein, wir brauchen keinen Polizisten.\nA: Der Polizist würde den Streit beenden.\nB: Hildi beendet den Streit schneller.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Should we call a policeman?\nB: No, we don't need a policeman.\nA: The policeman would end the argument.\nB: Hildi ends the argument faster.",funFact:"[AR] From 'Polizei' (police). Weak masculine noun (N-Deklination): den Polizisten, dem Polizisten. 'Die Polizei rufen' (to call the police)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Polizistin",src:"[AR] the policewoman",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Polizist + -in. About 30% of German police officers are women.\nThe feminine -in suffix you know from Unit 1.",example:"A: Die Polizistin war sehr nett.\nB: Welche Polizistin?\nA: Die Polizistin, die letzte Woche hier war.\nB: Ach, wegen des Lärms?",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The policewoman was very nice.\nB: Which policewoman?\nA: The policewoman who was here last week.\nB: Oh, because of the noise?",funFact:"[AR] Polizist + -in. The feminine -in suffix is always added for female professionals. About 30% of German police officers are women, and rising."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Richter",src:"[AR] the judge",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] From 'richten' (to direct/judge). Vor dem Richter stehen = to stand before the judge.\nGerman judges do not use gavels.",example:"A: Hildi ist wie ein Richter.\nB: Sie ist kein Richter, sie ist Nachbarin.\nA: Aber sie urteilt wie ein Richter.\nB: Ein Richter mit Lesebrille und Tee.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Hildi is like a judge.\nB: She's no judge, she's a neighbor.\nA: But she judges like a judge.\nB: A judge with reading glasses and tea.",funFact:"[AR] From 'richten' (to direct/judge). German judges do not use gavels. They simply say 'Im Namen des Volkes' (In the name of the people)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Richterin",src:"[AR] the female judge",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Richter + -in. Germany's highest court has had several Richterinnen.\nThe -in suffix is always added for female professionals.",example:"A: Die Richterin hat das Urteil gesprochen.\nB: Was hat die Richterin gesagt?\nA: Die Richterin sagt: beide haben Recht.\nB: Eine weise Richterin.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The judge delivered the verdict.\nB: What did the judge say?\nA: The judge says: both are right.\nB: A wise judge.",funFact:"[AR] Richter + -in. Germany's highest court (Bundesverfassungsgericht) has had several Richterinnen. The -in suffix is always added for female professionals."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Anwalt",src:"[AR] the lawyer",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] From Old High German 'anawalt' (representative).\nEinen Anwalt nehmen = to get a lawyer.",example:"A: Brauchst du einen Anwalt?\nB: Einen Anwalt? Wegen eines Streits?\nA: Man weiß nie.\nB: Hildi ist billiger als jeder Anwalt.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Do you need a lawyer?\nB: A lawyer? Because of an argument?\nA: You never know.\nB: Hildi is cheaper than any lawyer.",funFact:"[AR] From Old High German 'anawalt' (representative). Germans have Rechtsschutzversicherung (legal insurance) because they sue so often. Well, so goes the stereotype."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Anwältin",src:"[AR] the female lawyer",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Anwalt + -in. Note: no Umlaut change.\nSome words Umlaut when adding -in, this one does not.",example:"A: Meine Anwältin sagt, ich habe Recht.\nB: Du hast eine Anwältin?\nA: Nein, Hildi spielt die Anwältin.\nB: Die beste Anwältin im Haus.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: My lawyer says I'm right.\nB: You have a lawyer?\nA: No, Hildi is playing the lawyer.\nB: The best lawyer in the building.",funFact:"[AR] Anwalt + -in. Note: some words Umlaut when adding -in (Arzt/Ärztin), others do not (Anwalt/Anwältin). This one does not."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Strafzettel",src:"[AR] the ticket, the fine",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] Strafe + Zettel (note/ticket). A punishment-note.\nEinen Strafzettel bekommen = to get a ticket.",example:"A: Verumius hat einen Strafzettel bekommen.\nB: Wofür?\nA: Falschparken.\nB: Erst Lärm, dann Falschparken. Was kommt als Nächstes?",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Verumius got a ticket.\nB: For what?\nA: Illegal parking.\nB: First noise, then illegal parking. What's next?",funFact:"[AR] Strafe + Zettel (note/ticket). A punishment-note. Parking tickets, noise violation notices. 'Einen Strafzettel bekommen' is a rite of passage in Germany."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Kriminalpolizei",src:"[AR] the criminal investigation department",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Kriminal + Polizei. Abbreviated: die Kripo.\nEvery German crime TV show features the Kripo.",example:"A: Brauchen wir die Kriminalpolizei?\nB: Die Kripo? Wegen eines Bohrlochs?\nA: Nein, natürlich nicht.\nB: Gut. Die Kriminalpolizei hat Besseres zu tun.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Do we need the criminal police?\nB: The Kripo? Because of a drill hole?\nA: No, of course not.\nB: Good. The criminal police have better things to do.",funFact:"[AR] Abbreviated: die Kripo. Handles serious crimes. Every German crime TV show (Tatort, anyone?) features the Kripo."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Prozess",src:"[AR] the trial, the process",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] From Latin 'processus.' Einen Prozess führen = to conduct a trial.\nAlso means process in general.",example:"A: Es wird keinen Prozess geben.\nB: Ein Prozess wegen Lärm?\nA: Nein, der Prozess der Versöhnung.\nB: Der wichtigste Prozess.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: There won't be a trial.\nB: A trial because of noise?\nA: No, the process of reconciliation.\nB: The most important process.",funFact:"[AR] From Latin 'processus.' 'Einen Prozess führen' (to conduct a trial). Also means process in general. Legal and general, one word."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"das Urteil",src:"[AR] the verdict, the judgment",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"[AR] Ur- (original/primal) + Teil (part). The original division.\nEin Urteil fällen = to pass judgment.",example:"A: Hildis Urteil war klar.\nB: Was war ihr Urteil?\nA: Beide Seiten müssen sich entschuldigen.\nB: Ein faires Urteil.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Hildi's verdict was clear.\nB: What was her verdict?\nA: Both sides must apologize.\nB: A fair verdict.",funFact:"[AR] Ur- (original/primal) + Teil (part). The original division: guilty or not guilty. 'Ein Urteil fällen' (to pass judgment). Also: opinion. 'Sich ein Urteil bilden.'"},
        {type:"story",speaker:"hildi",mood:"matter-of-fact",art:"de-ber-hildi-livingroom-hausordnung",trg:"Paragraph drei, Absatz zwei: Ruhestörender Lärm ist ab 20 Uhr untersagt. Verumius, du hast um 20:05 gebohrt. Fünf Minuten zu spät.",src:"[AR] Paragraph three, section two: Disturbing noise is prohibited after 8 PM. Verumius, you drilled at 8:05. Five minutes too late."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"das Risiko",src:"[AR] the risk",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"[AR] From Italian 'risico.' Plural: Risiken.\nEin Risiko eingehen = to take a risk.",example:"A: Es war ein Risiko, am Sonntag zu bohren.\nB: Ja, ein großes Risiko.\nA: Das Risiko hat sich nicht gelohnt.\nB: Nächstes Mal: kein Risiko.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: It was a risk to drill on Sunday.\nB: Yes, a big risk.\nA: The risk didn't pay off.\nB: Next time: no risk.",funFact:"[AR] From Italian 'risico.' Plural: Risiken (not Risikos). 'Ein Risiko eingehen' (to take a risk). Drilling on Sunday was definitely ein Risiko."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Verdacht",src:"[AR] the suspicion",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] From 'verdächtig' (suspicious). Unter Verdacht stehen = to be under suspicion.\nVerdacht schöpfen = to grow suspicious.",example:"A: Der Nachbar hat einen Verdacht.\nB: Welchen Verdacht?\nA: Dass Verumius auch unter der Woche bohrt.\nB: Das ist ein falscher Verdacht!",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbor has a suspicion.\nB: What suspicion?\nA: That Verumius also drills during the week.\nB: That's a false suspicion!",funFact:"[AR] 'Unter Verdacht stehen' (to be under suspicion). 'Verdacht schöpfen' (to grow suspicious, literally to scoop suspicion). Used in crime shows constantly."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"verdächtig",src:"[AR] suspicious",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] From Verdacht. Das ist verdächtig = That is suspicious.\nSich verdächtig machen = to make oneself look suspicious.",example:"A: Das ist verdächtig.\nB: Was ist verdächtig?\nA: Dass der Nachbar plötzlich freundlich ist.\nB: Freundlichkeit ist nicht verdächtig!",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: That is suspicious.\nB: What is suspicious?\nA: That the neighbor is suddenly friendly.\nB: Friendliness is not suspicious!",funFact:"[AR] From Verdacht. 'Das ist verdächtig' (That is suspicious). 'Sich verdächtig machen' (to make oneself look suspicious). Crime show vocabulary, now in your apartment."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"strafbar",src:"[AR] punishable",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Strafe + -bar. Strafbare Handlung = punishable act.\nDrilling during Ruhezeit is technically strafbar.",example:"A: Ist Lärm während der Ruhezeit strafbar?\nB: Theoretisch ja, das ist strafbar.\nA: Wie strafbar?\nB: Geldbuße bis fünfhundert Euro.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Is noise during quiet hours punishable?\nB: Theoretically yes, that is punishable.\nA: How punishable?\nB: Fine up to five hundred euros.",funFact:"[AR] Strafe + -bar. Drilling during Ruhezeit is technically strafbar in some municipalities. Usually just gets you a stern note."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"gerecht",src:"[AR] just, fair",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'Recht' (right/law). Gerechtigkeit = justice.\nFormal version of 'fair.'",example:"A: Hildis Urteil war gerecht.\nB: War es wirklich gerecht?\nA: Ja, beide Seiten waren zufrieden.\nB: Dann war es gerecht.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Hildi's verdict was just.\nB: Was it really fair?\nA: Yes, both sides were satisfied.\nB: Then it was fair.",funFact:"[AR] From 'Recht' (right/law). 'Gerechtigkeit' (justice). Hildi wants a gerechtes Urteil. 'Gerecht und fair' uses both the German and the borrowed English word."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"unentschieden",src:"[AR] undecided, tied",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Un- + entschieden (decided). Das Spiel endete unentschieden.\nIn the neighbor dispute: both sides have valid points.",example:"A: Wer hat gewonnen?\nB: Unentschieden.\nA: In einem Streit gibt es kein Unentschieden.\nB: Bei Hildi schon. Beide haben Recht.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Who won?\nB: A draw.\nA: In an argument there's no draw.\nB: With Hildi there is. Both are right.",funFact:"[AR] Un- + entschieden (decided). 'Das Spiel endete unentschieden' (The match ended in a draw). In the neighbor dispute: both sides have valid points. Unentschieden."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"gespannt",src:"[AR] excited, eager, tense",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'spannen' (to tense). Ich bin gespannt! = I'm curious/excited!\nLike a rubber band pulled tight with anticipation.",example:"A: Ich bin gespannt auf das Ergebnis.\nB: Wir sind alle gespannt.\nA: Gespannt wie ein Flitzebogen.\nB: Die Stimmung ist gespannt.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: I'm eager about the result.\nB: We're all eager.\nA: Tense as a bowstring.\nB: The atmosphere is tense.",funFact:"[AR] From 'spannen' (to tense). Like a rubber band pulled tight with anticipation. 'Gespannt warten' (to wait eagerly). Both positive (excited) and negative (tense) meaning."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"ängstlich",src:"[AR] anxious, fearful",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'Angst' (fear/anxiety). Ängstlich sein = to be fearful.\nThe English word 'angst' was borrowed from German.",example:"A: Verumius ist ängstlich.\nB: Warum ängstlich?\nA: Er fürchtet die Reaktion des Nachbarn.\nB: Sei nicht so ängstlich. Hildi ist dabei.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Verumius is anxious.\nB: Why anxious?\nA: He fears the neighbor's reaction.\nB: Don't be so anxious. Hildi is there.",funFact:"[AR] From 'Angst' (fear/anxiety). The English word 'angst' was borrowed directly from German. You already know a world-famous German word."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"einsam",src:"[AR] lonely",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'ein' (one) + -sam (tendency suffix). One-tending.\nSich einsam fühlen = to feel lonely.",example:"A: Der Nachbar fühlt sich vielleicht einsam.\nB: Einsam? Er hat doch seine Frau.\nA: Einsam trotzdem. Einsam kann man auch zu zweit sein.\nB: Tiefe Worte für einen Zettelkrieg.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbor maybe feels lonely.\nB: Lonely? He has his wife.\nA: Lonely anyway. You can be lonely even as a pair.\nB: Deep words for a note war.",funFact:"[AR] From 'ein' (one) + -sam (tendency suffix). One-tending. Someone who tends toward being alone. The neighbor might be einsam, hence the complaints."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"guilty",art:"de-ber-hildi-livingroom-mediation",trg:"Hildi hatte recht. Ich habe nicht nachgedacht. Fünf Minuten nach acht, ein Sonntag, und ich stehe da mit meiner Bohrmaschine wie ein Verbrecher.",src:"[AR] Hildi was right. I did not think. Five minutes past eight, a Sunday, and I stand there with my drill like a criminal."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"stolz",src:"[AR] proud",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Stolz auf etwas sein = to be proud of something.\nTakes auf + accusative.",example:"A: Hildi ist stolz auf ihre Mediation.\nB: Sie kann stolz sein.\nA: Ich bin stolz auf dich, Hildi.\nB: Danke. Ich bin stolz auf euch alle.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Hildi is proud of her mediation.\nB: She can be proud.\nA: I'm proud of you, Hildi.\nB: Thanks. I'm proud of all of you.",funFact:"[AR] 'Stolz auf etwas sein' (to be proud of something). Takes auf + accusative. 'Ich bin stolz auf dich' (I am proud of you). A word Hildi uses after successful mediation."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"mutig",src:"[AR] courageous, brave",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'Mut' (courage). Mutig sein = to be brave.\nThe -ig ending turns nouns into adjectives: Mut -> mutig.",example:"A: Das war mutig von dir.\nB: Mutig? Ich hatte Angst.\nA: Trotzdem mutig. Mut ist Handeln trotz Angst.\nB: Dann war ich sehr mutig.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: That was brave of you.\nB: Brave? I was scared.\nA: Brave anyway. Courage is acting despite fear.\nB: Then I was very brave.",funFact:"[AR] From 'Mut' (courage). The -ig ending turns nouns into adjectives: Mut -> mutig, Schuld -> schuldig, Hunger -> hungrig. A productive pattern."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"kämpfen",src:"[AR] to fight, to struggle",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'Kampf' (fight/battle). Für etwas kämpfen = to fight for something.\nRelated to English 'camp' (military).",example:"A: Er kämpft für seine Ruhe.\nB: Und Verumius kämpft für sein Regal.\nA: Beide kämpfen für das Richtige.\nB: Wenn alle kämpfen, braucht man Hildi.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: He fights for his peace.\nB: And Verumius fights for his shelf.\nA: Both fight for the right thing.\nB: When everyone fights, you need Hildi.",funFact:"[AR] From 'Kampf' (fight/battle). 'Für etwas kämpfen' (to fight for something). Related to Latin 'campus' (field, as in battlefield)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"schließlich",src:"[AR] finally, after all",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'schließen' (to close). The closing word of an argument.\n'Schließlich hat er Recht' means 'After all, he is right.'",example:"A: Schließlich hat Hildi recht.\nB: Ja, schließlich kennt sie die Regeln.\nA: Schließlich wohnt sie hier am längsten.\nB: Schließlich sind wir alle Nachbarn.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: After all, Hildi is right.\nB: Yes, after all, she knows the rules.\nA: After all, she's lived here the longest.\nB: After all, we're all neighbors.",funFact:"[AR] From 'schließen' (to close). The closing word of an argument. 'Schließlich' signals the final point. Used constantly in everyday reasoning."},
        {type:"mc",q:"Hildi fragt: 'Wissen Sie, ob das wirklich _____ ist?'",opts:["gespannt","dankbar","einsam","strafbar"],ans:"strafbar",hint:"[AR] Hildi checks the legal status. Which word describes an action that can be punished?"},
        {type:"fb",s:"Nachdem Hildi das Urteil gesprochen {1}, waren beide Nachbarn zufrieden.",a:["hatte"],opts:["hatte","hat","ist","war"],hint:"[AR] Nachdem requires Plusquamperfekt: auxiliary + past participle. The auxiliary for 'sprechen' is 'haben.'",sSrc:"[AR] After Hildi had spoken the verdict, both neighbors were satisfied."},
        {type:"mc",q:"Verumius möchte wissen, ob der Nachbar ihm verzeihen kann. Welche indirekte Frage ist korrekt?",opts:[
            "Er fragt, ob der Nachbar ihm verzeihen können.",
            "Er fragt, ob der Nachbar ihm verzeihen kann.",
            "Er fragt, ob kann der Nachbar ihm verzeihen.",
            "Er fragt, der Nachbar ob ihm verzeihen kann."
          ],ans:"Er fragt, ob der Nachbar ihm verzeihen kann.",hint:"[AR] After 'ob,' the conjugated verb goes to the end of the subordinate clause."},
        {type:"match",pairs:[
            {trg:"Polizist",src:"policeman"},
            {trg:"Richterin",src:"female judge"},
            {trg:"Anwalt",src:"lawyer"},
            {trg:"Urteil",src:"verdict"},
            {trg:"Risiko",src:"risk"},
            {trg:"Prozess",src:"trial"}
          ]},
        {type:"story",speaker:"hildi",mood:"firm-but-warm",art:"de-ber-hildi-livingroom-verdict",trg:"Mein Urteil: Verumius entschuldigt sich. Der Nachbar akzeptiert. Und am Sonntag wird nicht gebohrt. Punkt.",src:"[AR] My verdict: Verumius apologizes. The neighbor accepts. And on Sundays there will be no drilling. Period."}
      ]},
    {id:"deu_r16l6",title:"Heinrichs Weisheit",icon:"📞",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Heinrichs Weisheit",desc:"[AR] Hildi calls Heinrich. He yells through the phone. But his wisdom is worth gold. Learn trust, betrayal, and ver- prefix verbs.",goals:[
            "[AR] Learn vocabulary for trust and betrayal",
            "[AR] Hear Heinrich's phone wisdom",
            "[AR] Combine nachdem + indirect questions in one sentence"
          ]},
        {type:"story",speaker:"hildi",mood:"warm",art:"de-ber-hildi-kitchen-phone",trg:"Warte, ich rufe Heinrich an. Er weiß immer, was man in solchen Situationen tun soll.",src:"[AR] Wait, I'll call Heinrich. He always knows what to do in situations like these."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"das Vertrauen",src:"[AR] the trust",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"[AR] From 'trauen' (to trust/dare). Vertrauen ist gut, Kontrolle ist besser.\nAttributed to Lenin, but Germans live by it.",example:"A: Vertrauen ist die Basis jeder Beziehung.\nB: Auch einer Nachbarschaft?\nA: Besonders einer Nachbarschaft.\nB: Vertrauen braucht Zeit.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Trust is the basis of every relationship.\nB: Even a neighborhood?\nA: Especially a neighborhood.\nB: Trust takes time.",funFact:"[AR] 'Vertrauen ist gut, Kontrolle ist besser' (Trust is good, control is better). Attributed to Lenin, but Germans live by it. Also the unofficial motto of the Hausordnung."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Verzeihung",src:"[AR] the forgiveness, the pardon",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] The noun from 'verzeihen.' Verzeihung! = formal apology.\nMore polished than 'Entschuldigung.'",example:"A: Verzeihung!\nB: Wofür bitten Sie um Verzeihung?\nA: Für den Lärm am Sonntag.\nB: Verzeihung angenommen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Pardon!\nB: What are you asking forgiveness for?\nA: For the noise on Sunday.\nB: Forgiveness accepted.",funFact:"[AR] More polished than 'Entschuldigung.' Used when bumping into someone at the opera, not at the supermarket. 'Verzeihung!' is a formal apology in one word."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Wunde",src:"[AR] the wound",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Both physical and emotional. Alte Wunden aufreißen = to reopen old wounds.\nThe neighbor dispute has left Wunden.",example:"A: Der Streit hat Wunden hinterlassen.\nB: Welche Wunden?\nA: Emotionale Wunden.\nB: Zeit heilt alle Wunden.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The argument has left wounds.\nB: What wounds?\nA: Emotional wounds.\nB: Time heals all wounds.",funFact:"[AR] Both physical and emotional. 'Alte Wunden aufreißen' (to reopen old wounds). 'Zeit heilt alle Wunden' (Time heals all wounds). The same proverb in both languages."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Träne",src:"[AR] the tear (teardrop)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Usually plural: Tränen. Tränen in den Augen = tears in the eyes.\nKrokodilstränen = crocodile tears.",example:"A: Tränen sind keine Schwäche.\nB: Hatte der Nachbar Tränen?\nA: Fast. Tränen lagen in der Luft.\nB: Tränen wegen eines Bohrlochs?",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Tears are not weakness.\nB: Did the neighbor have tears?\nA: Almost. Tears were in the air.\nB: Tears because of a drill hole?",funFact:"[AR] Usually plural: Tränen. 'Krokodilstränen' (crocodile tears) exists in German too. Same metaphor, same skepticism."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"das Unglück",src:"[AR] the misfortune, the accident",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"[AR] Un- + Glück (luck/happiness). Ein Unglück kommt selten allein.\nThe opposite of everything good.",example:"A: Ein Unglück kommt selten allein.\nB: Was für ein Unglück?\nA: Erst der Streit, dann das Klären.\nB: Das ist kein Unglück, das ist das Leben.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Misfortune rarely comes alone.\nB: What misfortune?\nA: First the argument, then the making up.\nB: That's not misfortune, that's life.",funFact:"[AR] Un- + Glück (luck/happiness). 'Ein Unglück kommt selten allein' (Misfortune rarely comes alone). Das Unglück. The opposite of everything good."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Schade",src:"[AR] the pity, the shame",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] Das ist schade = That is a pity. Also an exclamation: Schade!\nOne of the most useful expressions of mild disappointment.",example:"A: Schade, dass es so gekommen ist.\nB: Ja, wirklich schade.\nA: Es ist ein Schade für alle.\nB: Aber kein bleibender Schade.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: What a pity it came to this.\nB: Yes, really a pity.\nA: It's a shame for everyone.\nB: But no lasting damage.",funFact:"[AR] 'Das ist schade' (That is a pity). Also an exclamation: 'Schade!' Used constantly in daily conversation. One of the most useful expressions of mild disappointment."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Schaden",src:"[AR] the damage",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] Different from Schade (pity). Einen Schaden verursachen = to cause damage.\n'Schadenfreude' is Germany's most famous export word.",example:"A: Gibt es einen Schaden?\nB: Nur ein kleines Loch in der Wand.\nA: Der Schaden ist gering.\nB: Gering, aber der Nachbar sieht das anders.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Is there any damage?\nB: Just a small hole in the wall.\nA: The damage is minor.\nB: Minor, but the neighbor sees it differently.",funFact:"[AR] Different from Schade (pity). 'Schadenfreude' (joy at others' misfortune) is Germany's most famous export word. 'Einen Schaden verursachen' = to cause damage."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Verlust",src:"[AR] the loss",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] From 'verlieren' (to lose). Einen Verlust erleiden = to suffer a loss.\nFinancial, personal, game loss. Der Verlust covers them all.",example:"A: Der Verlust von Vertrauen ist das Schlimmste.\nB: Ja, ein großer Verlust.\nA: Aber Vertrauen kann man wieder aufbauen.\nB: Nach jedem Verlust kommt ein Neuanfang.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The loss of trust is the worst.\nB: Yes, a great loss.\nA: But trust can be rebuilt.\nB: After every loss comes a new beginning.",funFact:"[AR] From 'verlieren' (to lose). 'Einen Verlust erleiden' (to suffer a loss). Financial loss, personal loss, game loss. Der Verlust covers them all."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"vertrauen",src:"[AR] to trust",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Jemandem vertrauen = to trust someone. Takes dative.\nIch vertraue dir = I trust you.",example:"A: Kannst du mir vertrauen?\nB: Ich vertraue dir.\nA: Wirklich? Du vertraust mir?\nB: Ja, ich vertraue dir. Aber bohre nicht mehr am Sonntag.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Can you trust me?\nB: I trust you.\nA: Really? You trust me?\nB: Yes, I trust you. But don't drill on Sunday anymore.",funFact:"[AR] 'Jemandem vertrauen' (to trust someone). Takes dative. 'Ich vertraue dir' (I trust you). The verb version of Vertrauen. Essential for any relationship."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"versprechen",src:"[AR] to promise",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: versprach, versprochen. Ich verspreche dir = I promise you.\nAlso: sich versprechen = to misspeak.",example:"A: Ich verspreche, nicht mehr am Sonntag zu bohren.\nB: Versprichst du das?\nA: Ich verspreche es.\nB: Ein Versprechen ist ein Versprechen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: I promise not to drill on Sunday anymore.\nB: Do you promise that?\nA: I promise.\nB: A promise is a promise.",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: versprach, versprochen. Also: 'sich versprechen' (to misspeak). Promise and mistake share a verb. Choose your prefix carefully."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"verraten",src:"[AR] to betray, to reveal",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: verriet, verraten. Ein Geheimnis verraten = to reveal a secret.\nJemanden verraten = to betray someone.",example:"A: Verrate mir, was Heinrich gesagt hat.\nB: Er hat ein Geheimnis verraten.\nA: Was hat er verraten?\nB: Dass Nachbarn wie Brot sind.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Tell me what Heinrich said.\nB: He revealed a secret.\nA: What did he reveal?\nB: That neighbors are like bread.",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: verriet, verraten. One verb for secrets shared and trust broken. 'Ein Geheimnis verraten' and 'Jemanden verraten' use the same word."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"heinrich",mood:"philosophical",art:"de-ber-phone-heinrich",trg:"Verumius, hör zu. Ich habe fünfzig Jahre lang Nachbarn gehabt. Manche waren laut, manche leise. Alle brauchten Geduld. Und Marmelade.",src:"[AR] Verumius, listen. I have had neighbors for fifty years. Some were loud, some quiet. All of them needed patience. And jam."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"verhalten",src:"[AR] to behave",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Sich verhalten = to behave/conduct oneself.\nIrregular: verhielt, verhalten.",example:"A: Wie soll ich mich verhalten?\nB: Verhalte dich ruhig und höflich.\nA: Ich habe mich schlecht verhalten.\nB: Dann ändere dein Verhalten.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: How should I behave?\nB: Behave calmly and politely.\nA: I behaved badly.\nB: Then change your behavior.",funFact:"[AR] 'Sich verhalten' (to behave/conduct oneself). Irregular: verhielt, verhalten. 'Wie soll ich mich verhalten?' (How should I behave?). The reflexive is essential."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"verhindern",src:"[AR] to prevent",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Einen Streit verhindern = to prevent an argument.\nDas konnte ich nicht verhindern = I couldn't prevent that.",example:"A: Kann man Streit verhindern?\nB: Man kann versuchen, Streit zu verhindern.\nA: Wie verhindern wir den nächsten Streit?\nB: Nicht am Sonntag bohren.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Can you prevent arguments?\nB: You can try to prevent arguments.\nA: How do we prevent the next argument?\nB: Don't drill on Sunday.",funFact:"[AR] Inseparable ver-. 'Das konnte ich nicht verhindern' (I could not prevent that). A key mediation word. Prevention is better than Streit."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"verlassen",src:"[AR] to leave, to abandon / to rely on",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: verließ, verlassen. Die Wohnung verlassen = to leave.\nSich auf jemanden verlassen = to rely on someone.",example:"A: Er hat das Zimmer verlassen.\nB: Kann man sich auf ihn verlassen?\nA: Ja, verlass dich auf Heinrich.\nB: Er hat uns noch nie verlassen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: He left the room.\nB: Can you rely on him?\nA: Yes, rely on Heinrich.\nB: He has never abandoned us.",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: verließ, verlassen. Two meanings: 'Die Wohnung verlassen' (to leave the apartment) and 'Sich auf jemanden verlassen' (to rely on someone). Leaving and relying: one verb."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"verlaufen",src:"[AR] to get lost, to go (of events)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] 'Sich verlaufen' means 'to lose one's way.'\n'Wie ist das Gespräch verlaufen?' means 'How did the conversation go?'",example:"A: Wie ist die Mediation verlaufen?\nB: Sie ist gut verlaufen.\nA: Ich habe mich fast verlaufen auf dem Weg zu Hildi.\nB: Verlaufen? Sie wohnt nebenan!",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: How did the mediation go?\nB: It went well.\nA: I almost got lost on the way to Hildi.\nB: Got lost? She lives next door!",funFact:"[AR] 'Sich verlaufen' (to lose one's way). 'Wie ist das Gespräch verlaufen?' (How did the conversation go?). Irregular like 'laufen.' Two very different uses."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"versäumen",src:"[AR] to miss, to neglect",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Eine Chance versäumen = to miss an opportunity.\nMore formal than 'verpassen.'",example:"A: Versäume nicht, dich zu entschuldigen.\nB: Ich werde es nicht versäumen.\nA: Wenn du es versäumst, wird es schlimmer.\nB: Keine Sorge, ich versäume es nicht.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Don't neglect to apologize.\nB: I won't neglect it.\nA: If you neglect it, it will get worse.\nB: Don't worry, I won't neglect it.",funFact:"[AR] More formal than 'verpassen.' 'Versäume nicht, dich zu entschuldigen' (Do not neglect to apologize). A verb for missed opportunities and unfulfilled duties."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"weigern",src:"[AR] to refuse",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Sich weigern = to refuse. Always reflexive.\nEr weigert sich, die Tür zu öffnen.",example:"A: Der Nachbar weigert sich zu reden.\nB: Er weigert sich?\nA: Ja, er weigert sich strikt.\nB: Dann muss Hildi ihn überzeugen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbor refuses to talk.\nB: He refuses?\nA: Yes, he strictly refuses.\nB: Then Hildi has to convince him.",funFact:"[AR] 'Sich weigern' (to refuse). Always reflexive. 'Er weigert sich, die Tür zu öffnen' (He refuses to open the door). The stubborn neighbor verb."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"zwingen",src:"[AR] to force",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: zwang, gezwungen. Strong word, strong verb.\n'Niemand kann dich zwingen' means 'Nobody can force you.'",example:"A: Man kann niemanden zum Frieden zwingen.\nB: Stimmt, Frieden kann man nicht erzwingen.\nA: Heinrich hat uns nicht gezwungen.\nB: Nein, er hat uns überzeugt.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: You can't force anyone into peace.\nB: True, peace can't be forced.\nA: Heinrich didn't force us.\nB: No, he convinced us.",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: zwang, gezwungen. 'Niemand kann dich zwingen' (Nobody can force you). 'Gezwungen' also means 'forced/stiff' as an adjective."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"ernsthaft",src:"[AR] seriously, earnest",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Ernst + -haft (having the quality of). Ernsthaft? = Seriously?\nStronger than 'ernst.'",example:"A: Ernsthaft?\nB: Ja, ernsthaft.\nA: Das ist eine ernsthafte Angelegenheit.\nB: Aber keine hoffnungslose.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Seriously?\nB: Yes, seriously.\nA: This is a serious matter.\nB: But not a hopeless one.",funFact:"[AR] Ernst + -haft (having the quality of). 'Ernsthaft?' (Seriously?). Stronger than 'ernst.' 'Eine ernsthafte Diskussion' (a serious discussion). The adjective for real, non-trivial matters."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"heimlich",src:"[AR] secretly",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'Heim' (home). Originally: homely, private. Now: secret, covert.\n'Das Unheimliche' (the uncanny) is Freud's famous term.",example:"A: Verumius hat heimlich Marmelade gekocht.\nB: Warum heimlich?\nA: Es soll eine Überraschung sein.\nB: Heimlich ist manchmal die beste Strategie.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Verumius secretly made jam.\nB: Why secretly?\nA: It's supposed to be a surprise.\nB: Secretly is sometimes the best strategy.",funFact:"[AR] From 'Heim' (home). Originally: homely, private. Now: secret, covert. 'Das Unheimliche' (the uncanny) is Freud's famous term. Home became secret became creepy."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"hildi",mood:"knowing",art:"de-ber-hildi-kitchen-phone",trg:"Heinrich hat aufgelegt, aber sein letzter Satz blieb im Raum: 'Geh zum Nachbarn. Nicht mit Worten. Mit etwas Selbstgemachtem.'",src:"[AR] Heinrich hung up, but his last sentence lingered in the room: 'Go to the neighbor. Not with words. With something homemade.'"},
        {type:"teach",trg:"hinterher",src:"[AR] afterwards, behind",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"[AR] Hinter (behind) + her (toward here). After the fact.\n'Hinterher ist man immer klüger' means 'Hindsight is 20/20.'",example:"A: Hinterher ist man immer klüger.\nB: Ja, hinterher weiß man alles besser.\nA: Hinterher hätte ich nicht gebohrt.\nB: Hinterher sagen alle das.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: In hindsight you're always smarter.\nB: Yes, afterwards you know everything better.\nA: In hindsight I wouldn't have drilled.\nB: Everyone says that afterwards.",funFact:"[AR] Hinter (behind) + her (toward here). 'Hinterher ist man immer klüger' (Hindsight is 20/20) is a German proverb. Literally: afterwards one is always smarter."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"eben",src:"[AR] just, exactly, precisely",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"[AR] Versatile Modalpartikel. Das ist eben so = That's just how it is.\nAlso means 'flat/level' as an adjective.",example:"A: Das ist eben Deutschland.\nB: Was meinst du mit 'eben'?\nA: Eben: so ist es halt.\nB: Regeln sind eben Regeln.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: That's just Germany.\nB: What do you mean by 'just'?\nA: Just: that's how it is.\nB: Rules are just rules.",funFact:"[AR] One of the most versatile Modalpartikeln. 'Das ist eben so' (That's just how it is). Expresses resigned acceptance. Also 'eben' = 'flat/level' and 'just now' (Ich war eben dort)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"stinken",src:"[AR] to stink",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: stank, gestunken. Same root as English 'stink.'\nDas stinkt mir = That annoys me (colloquial).",example:"A: Der Müll stinkt.\nB: Ja, er stinkt seit drei Tagen.\nA: Und die Situation stinkt auch.\nB: Alles stinkt. Wir brauchen frische Luft.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The trash stinks.\nB: Yes, it has been stinking for three days.\nA: And the situation stinks too.\nB: Everything stinks. We need fresh air.",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: stank, gestunken. Same root as English 'stink.' 'Das stinkt mir' (That annoys me) uses the verb figuratively. Both literal and emotional stench."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"heinrich",mood:"warm-and-loud",art:"de-ber-phone-heinrich",trg:"Nachbarn sind wie Brot. Man braucht sie jeden Tag!",src:"[AR] Neighbors are like bread. You need them every day!"},
        {type:"mc",q:"Nachdem Heinrich angerufen hatte, wollte Verumius wissen, ob er dem Nachbarn _____ konnte.",opts:["zwingen","vertrauen","weigern","verraten"],ans:"vertrauen",hint:"[AR] Which verb means 'to believe someone and rely on them'? It takes the dative."}
      ]},
    {id:"deu_r16l7",title:"Alles auf den Tisch",icon:"📚",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Alles auf den Tisch",desc:"[AR] Time for the test. Can you sequence events with 'nachdem' and ask polite indirect questions? Prove it. Learn crime vocabulary along the way.",goals:[
            "[AR] Test all grammar and vocabulary from Unit 16",
            "[AR] Demonstrate that you have mastered nachdem and indirect questions",
            "[AR] Learn crime vocabulary in context"
          ]},
        {type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"suspenseful",art:"de-ber-apartment-evening",trg:"Die Verhandlung war vorbei, aber der Streit war noch nicht ganz gelöst. Hildi hatte vermittelt. Heinrich hatte geschrien. Jetzt musste Verumius handeln.",src:"[AR] The negotiation was over, but the conflict was not quite resolved. Hildi had mediated. Heinrich had yelled. Now Verumius had to act."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Dieb",src:"[AR] the thief",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] Same root as English 'thief' (Proto-Germanic). Plural: Diebe.\nHaltet den Dieb! = Stop the thief!",example:"A: Ein Dieb war im Haus!\nB: Ein Dieb? Was hat er gestohlen?\nA: Nichts. Er hat nur die Zettel gelesen.\nB: Ein Dieb, der Zettel liest?",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: A thief was in the building!\nB: A thief? What did he steal?\nA: Nothing. He only read the notes.\nB: A thief who reads notes?",funFact:"[AR] Same root as English 'thief' (Proto-Germanic *theubaz). Der Dieb, plural: Diebe. 'Haltet den Dieb!' is from fairy tales and crime reports alike."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Einbrecher",src:"[AR] the burglar",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] Ein (in) + brechen (break) + -er (person). Someone who breaks in.\nDer Einbrecher kam durch das Fenster.",example:"A: War es ein Einbrecher?\nB: Nein, kein Einbrecher. Nur der Nachbar.\nA: Der Nachbar als Einbrecher?\nB: Er hat die Tür verwechselt.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Was it a burglar?\nB: No, no burglar. Just the neighbor.\nA: The neighbor as a burglar?\nB: He confused the door.",funFact:"[AR] Ein (in) + brechen (break) + -er (person). Someone who breaks in. 'Der Einbrecher kam durch das Fenster' is how crime reports begin."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Einbrecherin",src:"[AR] the female burglar",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Einbrecher + -in. Die Einbrecherin.\nCrime is equal-opportunity in German grammar.",example:"A: Die Einbrecherin wurde gefasst.\nB: Eine Einbrecherin?\nA: Ja, die Einbrecherin war sehr geschickt.\nB: Geschickt, aber nicht geschickt genug.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The female burglar was caught.\nB: A female burglar?\nA: Yes, the burglar was very skilled.\nB: Skilled, but not skilled enough.",funFact:"[AR] Einbrecher + -in. German always offers the feminine form. Crime is an equal-opportunity employer in grammar."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Einbruch",src:"[AR] the burglary, the break-in",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] The noun from 'einbrechen.' Also: Einbruch der Dunkelheit = nightfall.\nTwo meanings: crime and twilight.",example:"A: Nach dem Einbruch war alles anders.\nB: Welcher Einbruch?\nA: Der Einbruch in die Nachbarwohnung.\nB: Bei Einbruch der Dunkelheit kam die Polizei.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: After the break-in everything was different.\nB: What break-in?\nA: The break-in at the neighboring apartment.\nB: At nightfall the police came.",funFact:"[AR] The noun from 'einbrechen.' 'Einbruch der Dunkelheit' means nightfall (literally: the breaking-in of darkness). Two meanings: crime and twilight."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"das Gefängnis",src:"[AR] the prison",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"[AR] From 'fangen' (to catch). Ge- + fang + -nis.\nThe -nis ending creates neuter nouns: Gefängnis, Ergebnis, Geheimnis.",example:"A: Im Gefängnis? Wegen Lärm?\nB: Niemand kommt ins Gefängnis wegen Lärm.\nA: Gut. Kein Gefängnis.\nB: Nur Marmelade.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: In prison? Because of noise?\nB: Nobody goes to prison for noise.\nA: Good. No prison.\nB: Just jam.",funFact:"[AR] From 'fangen' (to catch). A place of catching. The -nis ending creates neuter nouns: Gefängnis, Ergebnis, Geheimnis."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Täter",src:"[AR] the perpetrator",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] From 'Tat' (deed/act). The one who does the deed.\nGender-neutral alternative: Täterperson.",example:"A: Wer ist der Täter?\nB: Verumius ist der Täter.\nA: Der Täter des Bohrlochs!\nB: Ein gefährlicher Täter mit Bohrmaschine.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Who is the perpetrator?\nB: Verumius is the perpetrator.\nA: The perpetrator of the drill hole!\nB: A dangerous perpetrator with a drill.",funFact:"[AR] From 'Tat' (deed/act). The one who does the deed. Legal and journalistic German. 'Der Täter floh' (The perpetrator fled)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Täterin",src:"[AR] the female perpetrator",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Täter + -in with Umlaut: Täterin.\nGerman legal language always specifies.",example:"A: Die Täterin ist bekannt.\nB: Eine Täterin?\nA: Ja, in diesem Fall war die Täterin eine Frau.\nB: Die Täterin wurde identifiziert.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The perpetrator is known.\nB: A female perpetrator?\nA: Yes, in this case the perpetrator was a woman.\nB: The perpetrator was identified.",funFact:"[AR] Täter + -in. Note the ä stays the same: Täterin. German legal language always specifies."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Tat",src:"[AR] the deed, the act, the crime",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Auf frischer Tat ertappt = caught in the act.\nIn der Tat = indeed (literally: in the deed).",example:"A: Was war die Tat?\nB: Bohren am Sonntag. Das ist die Tat.\nA: In der Tat eine schlimme Tat.\nB: Er wurde auf frischer Tat ertappt.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: What was the deed?\nB: Drilling on Sunday. That's the deed.\nA: Indeed a terrible deed.\nB: He was caught in the act.",funFact:"[AR] 'Auf frischer Tat ertappt' (caught in the act). 'In der Tat' (indeed). Small word, enormous range. From crime to emphasis."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Verbrecher",src:"[AR] the criminal",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] From 'verbrechen' (to commit a crime). Ver- + brechen (break).\nStronger than Dieb: any serious criminal.",example:"A: Verumius ist kein Verbrecher.\nB: Nein, ein Verbrecher bohrt nachts.\nA: Verumius bohrt nur am Sonntagabend.\nB: Kein Verbrecher, aber kein guter Nachbar.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Verumius is no criminal.\nB: No, a criminal drills at night.\nA: Verumius only drills on Sunday evening.\nB: No criminal, but not a good neighbor.",funFact:"[AR] From 'verbrechen' (to commit a crime). Ver- + brechen (break). Someone who breaks the law. Stronger than Dieb: any serious criminal."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Verbrecherin",src:"[AR] the female criminal",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Verbrecher + -in. Die Verbrecherin.\nThe pattern: masculine + -in = feminine role.",example:"A: Die Verbrecherin wurde gefasst.\nB: Welche Verbrecherin?\nA: Die vom Einbruch gestern.\nB: Gut, dass die Verbrecherin gefasst wurde.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The criminal was caught.\nB: Which criminal?\nA: The one from yesterday's burglary.\nB: Good that the criminal was caught.",funFact:"[AR] Verbrecher + -in. The pattern is always the same: masculine + -in = feminine profession or role."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Verlierer",src:"[AR] the loser",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] From 'verlieren' (to lose). Ein guter Verlierer sein = to be a good loser.\nIn the neighbor dispute, nobody wants to be the Verlierer.",example:"A: Wer ist der Verlierer?\nB: Niemand. Es gibt keinen Verlierer.\nA: Dann sind wir beide Gewinner?\nB: Genau. Kein Verlierer, zwei Gewinner.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Who is the loser?\nB: Nobody. There is no loser.\nA: Then we're both winners?\nB: Exactly. No loser, two winners.",funFact:"[AR] From 'verlieren' (to lose). 'Ein guter Verlierer sein' (to be a good loser). In the neighbor dispute, nobody wants to be the Verlierer."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"determined",art:"de-ber-apartment-thinking",trg:"Hildi sagte, ein Kompromiss braucht zwei Seiten. Der Nachbar hat seine Seite gezeigt. Jetzt bin ich dran.",src:"[AR] Hildi said a compromise needs two sides. The neighbor showed his side. Now it is my turn."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"festnehmen",src:"[AR] to arrest",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Fest (firm) + nehmen (take). Separable: Die Polizei nimmt ihn fest.\nMore official than 'verhaften.'",example:"A: Die Polizei hat den Dieb festgenommen.\nB: Wann haben sie ihn festgenommen?\nA: Gestern Nacht.\nB: Gut, dass sie ihn festgenommen haben.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The police arrested the thief.\nB: When did they arrest him?\nA: Last night.\nB: Good that they arrested him.",funFact:"[AR] Fest (firm) + nehmen (take). Separable: 'Die Polizei nimmt ihn fest.' To take someone firmly. More official than 'verhaften.'"},
        {type:"teach",trg:"verhaften",src:"[AR] to arrest",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'Haft' (custody). Inseparable ver-.\nEr wurde verhaftet = He was arrested.",example:"A: Der Einbrecher wurde verhaftet.\nB: Warum wurde er verhaftet?\nA: Wegen Einbruchs.\nB: Verhaftet und verurteilt?",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The burglar was arrested.\nB: Why was he arrested?\nA: For burglary.\nB: Arrested and convicted?",funFact:"[AR] From 'Haft' (custody). Inseparable ver-. 'Er wurde verhaftet' (He was arrested). Used interchangeably with festnehmen in daily speech."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"verurteilen",src:"[AR] to convict, to sentence",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'Urteil' (verdict). Zu drei Jahren verurteilt = sentenced to three years.\nThe legal climax of any Prozess.",example:"A: Der Richter hat ihn verurteilt.\nB: Wozu wurde er verurteilt?\nA: Zu einer Geldstrafe.\nB: Verurteilt wegen Lärm? Unglaublich.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The judge convicted him.\nB: What was he sentenced to?\nA: A fine.\nB: Convicted for noise? Unbelievable.",funFact:"[AR] From 'Urteil' (verdict). 'Zu drei Jahren verurteilt' (sentenced to three years). The legal climax of any Prozess."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"fangen",src:"[AR] to catch",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: fing, gefangen. 'Fang!' = Catch!\nChildren play 'Fangen' (tag). 'Anfangen' = to begin.",example:"A: Fang den Dieb!\nB: Ich kann ihn nicht fangen.\nA: Die Polizei hat ihn gefangen.\nB: Gefangen ist gefangen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Catch the thief!\nB: I can't catch him.\nA: The police caught him.\nB: Caught is caught.",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: fing, gefangen. Children play 'Fangen' (tag). 'Anfangen' (to begin, literally: to catch on). The caught one is 'gefangen.'"},
        {type:"teach",trg:"stehlen",src:"[AR] to steal",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: stahl, gestohlen. Same root as English 'steal.'\nJemandem die Show stehlen = to steal someone's show.",example:"A: Der Dieb hat nichts gestohlen.\nB: Was? Er hat nichts gestohlen?\nA: Nein. Er hat nur die Marmelade probiert.\nB: Marmelade stehlen zählt auch!",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The thief didn't steal anything.\nB: What? He didn't steal anything?\nA: No. He only tried the jam.\nB: Stealing jam counts too!",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: stahl, gestohlen. Same root as English 'steal.' 'Jemandem die Show stehlen' works in German too."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"schießen",src:"[AR] to shoot",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: schoss, geschossen. Ein Tor schießen = to score a goal.\nUsed in football, crime, and photography.",example:"A: Er hat ein Tor geschossen!\nB: Im Fußball? Oder mit der Kamera?\nA: Ein Foto geschossen. Vom Zettel.\nB: Man schießt Tore und Fotos. Interessant.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: He scored a goal!\nB: In football? Or with a camera?\nA: Shot a photo. Of the note.\nB: You shoot goals and photos. Interesting.",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: schoss, geschossen. 'Ein Tor schießen' (to score a goal). Used in football, crime, and photography ('ein Foto schießen')."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"greifen",src:"[AR] to grab, to grasp",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: griff, gegriffen. Nach etwas greifen = to reach for something.\nBegreifen = to comprehend (to grasp mentally).",example:"A: Greif dir die Marmelade.\nB: Ich greife nach dem Glas.\nA: Er hat nach der Türklinke gegriffen.\nB: Greifen, nicht reißen!",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Grab the jam.\nB: I'm reaching for the jar.\nA: He reached for the door handle.\nB: Grab, don't pull!",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: griff, gegriffen. 'Begreifen' (to comprehend) = to grasp mentally. 'Zugreifen' = to help oneself (at a buffet). One root, many meanings."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"einbrechen",src:"[AR] to break in, to burglarize",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Separable: Er bricht ein. Irregular: brach ein, eingebrochen.\nAlso: Einbruch der Dunkelheit = nightfall.",example:"A: Jemand ist eingebrochen!\nB: Wo ist er eingebrochen?\nA: In die Wohnung nebenan.\nB: Er ist durch das Fenster eingebrochen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Someone broke in!\nB: Where did they break in?\nA: Into the apartment next door.\nB: They broke in through the window.",funFact:"[AR] Separable: 'Er bricht ein.' Irregular: brach ein, eingebrochen. Also used metaphorically: 'Das Eis bricht ein' (the ice breaks). From ein (in) + brechen (break)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Streik",src:"[AR] the strike (labor)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] From English 'strike.' Borrowed during the Industrial Revolution.\nIn den Streik treten = to go on strike.",example:"A: Die Müllabfuhr ist im Streik.\nB: Seit wann dauert der Streik?\nA: Seit einer Woche.\nB: Ein Streik bedeutet volle Mülltonnen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The garbage collectors are on strike.\nB: How long has the strike lasted?\nA: For a week.\nB: A strike means full trash cans.",funFact:"[AR] From English 'strike.' The noun form of 'streiken.' Deutsche Bahn strikes are so legendary they have their own memes. 'Generalstreik' (general strike) shaped German labor history."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"unterlassen",src:"[AR] to refrain from, to cease",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Unter + lassen (let). Inseparable. Unterlassen Sie das! = Stop doing that!\nLegal tone: 'Unterlassungserklärung' = cease-and-desist.",example:"A: Unterlassen Sie das Bohren am Sonntag!\nB: Ich werde es unterlassen.\nA: Sie müssen es unterlassen.\nB: Versprochen. Ich unterlasse es.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Cease the drilling on Sunday!\nB: I will refrain from it.\nA: You must refrain from it.\nB: Promised. I'll cease.",funFact:"[AR] Unter + lassen (let). Inseparable. 'Unterlassen Sie das!' is formal for 'Stop doing that!' 'Unterlassungserklärung' (cease-and-desist letter) is the legal nuclear option in neighbor disputes."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"schütteln",src:"[AR] to shake",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Den Kopf schütteln = to shake one's head (means 'no' in Germany).\nHände schütteln = to shake hands.",example:"A: Er schüttelt den Kopf.\nB: Warum schüttelt er den Kopf?\nA: Er schüttelt den Kopf über den Lärm.\nB: Dann schütteln wir ihm die Hand und entschuldigen uns.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: He shakes his head.\nB: Why is he shaking his head?\nA: He's shaking his head about the noise.\nB: Then let's shake his hand and apologize.",funFact:"[AR] 'Den Kopf schütteln' (to shake one's head) means 'no' in Germany. 'Hände schütteln' (to shake hands) is the classic German greeting. One verb, two social rituals."},
        {type:"mc",q:"Nachdem der Dieb das Fenster geöffnet _____, stieg er in die Wohnung.",opts:["hatte","ist","hat","war"],ans:"hatte",hint:"[AR] Nachdem clause = Plusquamperfekt. Which auxiliary verb goes with 'geöffnet'?"},
        {type:"fb",s:"Können Sie mir sagen, {1} der Täter geflohen ist?",a:["wohin"],opts:["wohin","ob","dass","woher"],hint:"[AR] The question targets a direction: which way did the perpetrator flee?",sSrc:"[AR] Can you tell me where the perpetrator fled to?"},
        {type:"mc",q:"Welcher Satz ist grammatisch korrekt?",opts:[
            "Nachdem er verhaftet worden war, der Richter fragte, ob er schuldig sei.",
            "Nachdem er verhaftet worden war, fragte der Richter, ob er schuldig ist?",
            "Nachdem er verhaftet worden war, fragte der Richter, ob er schuldig sei.",
            "Nach er verhaftet worden war, der Richter fragte ob er schuldig war."
          ],ans:"Nachdem er verhaftet worden war, fragte der Richter, ob er schuldig sei.",hint:"[AR] Nachdem + Plusquamperfekt in the subordinate clause, then main clause verb in second position, then ob + verb at the end."},
        {type:"match",pairs:[
            {trg:"Dieb",src:"thief"},
            {trg:"Einbruch",src:"burglary"},
            {trg:"Gefängnis",src:"prison"},
            {trg:"Urteil",src:"verdict"},
            {trg:"Täter",src:"perpetrator"},
            {trg:"Verlierer",src:"loser"}
          ]},
        {type:"drag_fill",s:"Nachdem die Polizei den Täter {1} hatte, wollte der Richter wissen, {2} er die Tat {3} hatte.",blanks:{"1":"festgenommen","2":"ob","3":"geplant"},pool:["festgenommen","ob","geplant","verhaftet","dass","gemacht"],hint:"[AR] Three blanks: the arrest verb (Partizip II), the yes/no connector, and the planning verb (Partizip II). All in a nachdem + Plusquamperfekt structure.",sSrc:"[AR] After the police had arrested the perpetrator, the judge wanted to know whether he had planned the deed."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"transitional",art:"de-ber-stairwell-evening",trg:"Die Fakten lagen auf dem Tisch. Die Grammatik saß. Aber zwischen Wissen und Handeln liegt manchmal ein Glas Marmelade.",src:"[AR] The facts were on the table. The grammar was solid. But between knowing and acting, sometimes there is a jar of jam."}
      ]},
    {id:"deu_r16l8",title:"Marmelade und Frieden",icon:"🍓",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Marmelade und Frieden",desc:"[AR] Verumius places a jar of jam in front of the door. The neighbor responds with pickles. This is how you solve conflicts in German: with preserving jars.",goals:[
            "[AR] Learn the final conflict vocabulary",
            "[AR] Experience the German art of the peace offering",
            "[AR] Reflect on Ruhezeit, Hausordnung, and neighbor culture"
          ]},
        {type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"warm",art:"de-ber-stairwell-jam",trg:"Nachdem Verumius lange nachgedacht hatte, stellte er ein Glas Marmelade vor die Tür des Nachbarn.",src:"[AR] After Verumius had thought for a long time, he placed a jar of jam at the neighbor's door."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"der Gegner",src:"[AR] the opponent",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"[AR] From 'gegen' (against). Sports opponent, debate adversary, or neighbor.\nEin fairer Gegner = a fair opponent.",example:"A: Der Nachbar war mein Gegner.\nB: Und jetzt?\nA: Jetzt ist er kein Gegner mehr.\nB: Von Gegner zu Nachbar. Ein guter Weg.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbor was my opponent.\nB: And now?\nA: Now he's no longer an opponent.\nB: From opponent to neighbor. A good path.",funFact:"[AR] From 'gegen' (against). Can be a sports opponent, a debate adversary, or a neighbor in a Streit. 'Ein fairer Gegner' is what Hildi made both sides become."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"die Langeweile",src:"[AR] the boredom",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"[AR] Lange (long) + Weile (while). A long while.\n'Mir ist langweilig' means 'I am bored.' 'Aus Langeweile' means 'out of boredom.'",example:"A: Aus Langeweile hat er Zettel geschrieben.\nB: Langeweile führt zu Zettelkrieg?\nA: Langeweile führt zu vielen Dingen.\nB: Dann braucht der Nachbar ein Hobby.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: He wrote notes out of boredom.\nB: Boredom leads to note wars?\nA: Boredom leads to many things.\nB: Then the neighbor needs a hobby.",funFact:"[AR] Lange (long) + Weile (while). A long while. The compound tells the whole story: time stretching painfully. 'Mir ist langweilig' is how every German child announces boredom."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"betrunken",src:"[AR] drunk",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Past participle of 'trinken' used as adjective.\nBetrunken Auto fahren = to drive drunk. Illegal everywhere.",example:"A: War der Nachbar betrunken?\nB: Nein, er war nüchtern. Und trotzdem wütend.\nA: Nüchtern und wütend ist schlimmer als betrunken.\nB: Da hast du recht.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Was the neighbor drunk?\nB: No, he was sober. And still angry.\nA: Sober and angry is worse than drunk.\nB: You're right about that.",funFact:"[AR] Past participle of 'trinken' used as adjective. 'Betrunken Auto fahren' is illegal everywhere. The participle-as-adjective pattern is very productive in German."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"geschieden",src:"[AR] divorced",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Past participle of 'scheiden.' Familienstand: geschieden.\nA legal status turned adjective.",example:"A: Ist der Nachbar geschieden?\nB: Nein, er ist verheiratet.\nA: Vielleicht bald geschieden, wenn er so weiter macht.\nB: Geschieden wegen Lärmstreit?",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Is the neighbor divorced?\nB: No, he's married.\nA: Maybe divorced soon, if he keeps this up.\nB: Divorced because of a noise dispute?",funFact:"[AR] Past participle of 'scheiden.' On German forms, Familienstand: geschieden. A legal status turned adjective."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"getrennt",src:"[AR] separated",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Past participle of 'trennen.' Sie leben getrennt = They live separately.\nGetrennt zahlen = to pay separately (at restaurants).",example:"A: Die zwei Nachbarn leben getrennt durch eine Wand.\nB: Getrennt, aber verbunden.\nA: Getrennt zahlen?\nB: Nein, die Marmelade ist gratis.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The two neighbors live separated by a wall.\nB: Separated, but connected.\nA: Pay separately?\nB: No, the jam is free.",funFact:"[AR] Past participle of 'trennen.' 'Getrennt zahlen' (to pay separately) at restaurants is very German. Every group dinner ends with this phrase."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"geheim",src:"[AR] secret",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] From 'Heim' (home). What stays at home, stays private.\nGeheimdienst = secret service. Geheimnis = secret (noun).",example:"A: Die Marmelade ist ein geheimes Rezept.\nB: Geheim? Von wem?\nA: Von Verumius. Es ist geheim.\nB: Ein geheimes Friedensangebot.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The jam is a secret recipe.\nB: Secret? From whom?\nA: From Verumius. It's secret.\nB: A secret peace offering.",funFact:"[AR] From 'Heim' (home). Originally: homely, private. Now: secret. 'Geheimdienst' (secret service). 'Geheimnis' (secret, the noun) you already know."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"schlank",src:"[AR] slim",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Positive connotation, unlike 'dünn' (thin) which can sound clinical.\nSchlank bleiben = to stay slim.",example:"A: Die Chance auf Frieden ist schlank.\nB: Schlank, aber nicht null.\nA: Wie Verumius nach drei Wochen nur Marmelade.\nB: Schlank und voller Hoffnung.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The chance for peace is slim.\nB: Slim, but not zero.\nA: Like Verumius after three weeks of only jam.\nB: Slim and full of hope.",funFact:"[AR] Positive connotation, unlike 'dünn' (thin). 'Schlank bleiben' (to stay slim) is a fitness goal. Used literally and metaphorically."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"schmal",src:"[AR] narrow",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Ein schmaler Weg = a narrow path. Different from 'eng' (tight).\nSchmal = visually narrow. Eng = physically tight.",example:"A: Der Flur ist sehr schmal.\nB: Zu schmal für zwei Marmeladengläser?\nA: Nein, für ein Glas reicht der schmale Flur.\nB: Ein schmaler Weg zum Frieden.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The hallway is very narrow.\nB: Too narrow for two jam jars?\nA: No, the narrow hallway fits one jar.\nB: A narrow path to peace.",funFact:"[AR] Different from 'eng' (tight). Schmal = visually narrow. Eng = physically tight. 'Schmale Schultern' (narrow shoulders). A word about appearance, not squeeze."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"schief",src:"[AR] crooked, askew",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Das Bild hängt schief = The picture hangs crooked.\nSchiefgehen = to go wrong. 'Es wird schon schiefgehen!' = ironic.",example:"A: Das Regal hängt schief.\nB: Natürlich hängt es schief. Das war ja das Problem.\nA: Schief, aber es hält.\nB: Schief und schief gelaufen.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The shelf hangs crooked.\nB: Of course it hangs crooked. That was the problem.\nA: Crooked, but it holds.\nB: Crooked and gone wrong.",funFact:"[AR] 'Schiefgehen' (to go wrong). 'Es wird schon schiefgehen!' is ironic encouragement: 'It will go wrong!' meaning 'What could go wrong?' Verumius's shelf was definitely schief."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"stumm",src:"[AR] mute, silent",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Stronger than 'still.' A stumm person cannot or will not speak.\nStummfilm = silent film.",example:"A: Der Nachbar war drei Tage stumm.\nB: Stumm? Kein Wort?\nA: Kein einziges Wort. Stumm wie ein Fisch.\nB: Dann kam die Marmelade.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbor was silent for three days.\nB: Silent? Not a word?\nA: Not a single word. Mute as a fish.\nB: Then came the jam.",funFact:"[AR] Stronger than 'still.' A stumm person cannot or will not speak. 'Stummfilm' (silent film). The neighbor was stumm for three days after the drill incident."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"reflective",art:"de-ber-apartment-kitchen-jam",trg:"Drei Tage Stille. Kein Klopfen, kein Zettel, kein Wort. Die Stille war schlimmer als der Streit. Also kochte ich Marmelade.",src:"[AR] Three days of silence. No knocking, no notes, no words. The silence was worse than the argument. So I made jam."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"selten",src:"[AR] rarely, rare",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Selten so gelacht = Rarely laughed so much.\nEin seltenes Buch = a rare book. 'Seltsam' comes from selten.",example:"A: Solche Nachbarn sind selten.\nB: Ja, gute Nachbarn sind selten.\nA: Selten, aber wertvoll.\nB: Wie seltene Bücher.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Such neighbors are rare.\nB: Yes, good neighbors are rare.\nA: Rare, but valuable.\nB: Like rare books.",funFact:"[AR] 'Selten so gelacht' (Rarely laughed so much). As adjective: 'ein seltenes Buch' (a rare book). 'Seltsam' (strange), which you know, comes from selten."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"unglaublich",src:"[AR] unbelievable, incredibly",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Un- + glaub (believe) + -lich. An intensifier in casual speech.\n'Das ist unglaublich' means 'That is unbelievable.'",example:"A: Die Marmelade ist unglaublich gut.\nB: Unglaublich? Wirklich?\nA: Ja, unglaublich lecker.\nB: Unglaublich, dass Marmelade Frieden bringt.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The jam is unbelievably good.\nB: Unbelievable? Really?\nA: Yes, incredibly delicious.\nB: Unbelievable that jam brings peace.",funFact:"[AR] Un- + glaub (believe) + -lich. An intensifier in casual speech. 'Das ist unglaublich' expresses shock, admiration, or disbelief. Triple use, one word."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"unheimlich",src:"[AR] uncanny, incredibly",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Un- + heimlich (homely). What is not homely is creepy.\nIn casual German: 'unheimlich gut' = incredibly good.",example:"A: Die Stille war unheimlich.\nB: Unheimlich still?\nA: Ja, unheimlich still. Drei Tage.\nB: Unheimlich, aber dann kam die Marmelade.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The silence was uncanny.\nB: Uncannily quiet?\nA: Yes, uncannily quiet. Three days.\nB: Uncanny, but then came the jam.",funFact:"[AR] Un- + heimlich (homely). Freud wrote about 'das Unheimliche.' In casual German: 'unheimlich gut' (incredibly good). Same word: creepy AND intensifier."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"verliebt",src:"[AR] in love",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Past participle of 'sich verlieben' (to fall in love).\nVerliebt sein = to be in love. Frisch verliebt = freshly in love.",example:"A: Verumius ist verliebt.\nB: In wen?\nA: In die Marmelade.\nB: Verliebt in Marmelade? Das ist sehr deutsch.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Verumius is in love.\nB: With whom?\nA: With the jam.\nB: In love with jam? That's very German.",funFact:"[AR] Past participle of 'sich verlieben.' 'Verliebt sein' (to be in love). After the jam peace offering, Verumius and the neighbor are not verliebt, but perhaps they are friends."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"vergeblich",src:"[AR] in vain, futile",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"[AR] Vergeblich warten = to wait in vain.\nFrom 'vergeben' (to forgive, to give away). Something given with no return.",example:"A: War die Mühe vergeblich?\nB: Nein, nicht vergeblich. Die Marmelade hat geholfen.\nA: Also nicht vergeblich!\nB: Nichts ist vergeblich, wenn Marmelade im Spiel ist.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Was the effort in vain?\nB: No, not in vain. The jam helped.\nA: So not in vain!\nB: Nothing is in vain when jam is involved.",funFact:"[AR] 'Vergeblich warten' (to wait in vain). From 'vergeben' (to forgive, to give away). Something given away with no return. 'Alle Mühe war vergeblich' (All effort was in vain)."},
        {type:"story",speaker:"neighbor",mood:"surprised",art:"de-ber-apartment-door-jar",trg:"Ein Glas Marmelade? Von dem Mann mit der Bohrmaschine? Er klopfte nicht. Er stellte es einfach hin und ging.",src:"[AR] A jar of jam? From the man with the drill? He did not knock. He simply placed it there and left."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"beißen",src:"[AR] to bite",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: biss, gebissen. Der Hund beißt = The dog bites.\nIn den sauren Apfel beißen = to bite the bullet.",example:"A: Beiß in die Marmelade.\nB: Man beißt nicht in Marmelade!\nA: In den sauren Apfel beißen?\nB: Lieber in süße Marmelade.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Bite into the jam.\nB: You don't bite into jam!\nA: Bite the bullet?\nB: Rather into sweet jam.",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: biss, gebissen. 'In den sauren Apfel beißen' (to bite the sour apple = to bite the bullet). Same idiom, different fruit."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"beschränken",src:"[AR] to limit, to restrict",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Sich beschränken auf = to limit oneself to.\nBeschränkt can mean 'limited' or 'narrow-minded.'",example:"A: Beschränke das Bohren auf Werktage.\nB: Ich beschränke mich.\nA: Beschränke dich auf die erlaubten Zeiten.\nB: Versprochen. Ich beschränke mich.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Limit the drilling to weekdays.\nB: I'll limit myself.\nA: Limit yourself to the allowed times.\nB: Promised. I'll limit myself.",funFact:"[AR] 'Sich beschränken auf' (to limit oneself to). 'Beschränkt' can mean 'limited' or 'narrow-minded.' 'Bahnubergang beschränkt' (railroad crossing with barrier)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"entlassen",src:"[AR] to release, to dismiss, to fire",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Ent- + lassen (let). Aus dem Krankenhaus entlassen = discharged.\nEntlassen werden = to be fired. Context decides.",example:"A: Der Streit ist entlassen.\nB: Man entlässt keinen Streit!\nA: Dann ist der Streit beendet.\nB: Besser. Entlassen klingt wie gekündigt.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The argument is dismissed.\nB: You don't dismiss an argument!\nA: Then the argument is over.\nB: Better. Dismissed sounds like fired.",funFact:"[AR] Ent- + lassen (let). 'Aus dem Krankenhaus entlassen' (discharged from hospital). 'Entlassen werden' (to be fired). Context determines whether it is freedom or unemployment."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"bestrafen",src:"[AR] to punish",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Be- + Strafe + -en. The be- prefix makes Strafe transitive.\nDie Hausordnung exists to bestrafen violators. In theory.",example:"A: Muss man Verumius bestrafen?\nB: Nein, er hat sich selbst bestraft.\nA: Wie hat er sich bestraft?\nB: Mit drei Tagen Schweigen vom Nachbarn.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Must Verumius be punished?\nB: No, he punished himself.\nA: How did he punish himself?\nB: With three days of silence from the neighbor.",funFact:"[AR] Be- + Strafe + -en. The be- prefix makes Strafe into a transitive verb. The Hausordnung exists to bestrafen violators. In theory."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"betrügen",src:"[AR] to cheat, to deceive",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"[AR] Irregular: betrog, betrogen. Jemanden betrügen = to cheat someone.\nBetrug = fraud (noun). A heavy word.",example:"A: Hat der Nachbar mich betrogen?\nB: Nein, er hat dich nicht betrogen.\nA: Er hat behauptet, ich bohre jeden Tag!\nB: Das ist keine Betrug, das ist Übertreibung.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Did the neighbor deceive me?\nB: No, he didn't deceive you.\nA: He claimed I drill every day!\nB: That's not fraud, that's exaggeration.",funFact:"[AR] Irregular: betrog, betrogen. In relationships and in business, a heavy word. 'Betrug' (fraud) is the noun. Trust broken, promises violated."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"auseinander",src:"[AR] apart, asunder",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"[AR] Aus (out) + einander (each other). Literally: out from each other.\nAuseinandergehen = to part ways. Auseinandersetzen = to discuss.",example:"A: Die Nachbarn gingen auseinander.\nB: Auseinander? Nach dem Streit?\nA: Ja, aber dann kamen sie wieder zusammen.\nB: Erst auseinander, dann zusammen. So ist das Leben.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: The neighbors parted ways.\nB: Apart? After the argument?\nA: Yes, but then they came back together.\nB: First apart, then together. That's life.",funFact:"[AR] Aus (out) + einander (each other). 'Sich auseinandersetzen mit' (to grapple with/discuss) is essential academic German. Literally: to sit apart from each other and think."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"heim",src:"[AR] home, homeward",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"[AR] Short for 'nach Hause.' Heimgehen = to go home.\nDas Heim = the home (noun). Heimat = homeland.",example:"A: Gehen wir heim.\nB: Ja, es ist spät. Heim mit uns.\nA: Heim ist, wo die Marmelade steht.\nB: Und die Bohrmaschine.",exampleSrc:"[AR] A: Let's go home.\nB: Yes, it's late. Home with us.\nA: Home is where the jam stands.\nB: And the drill.",funFact:"[AR] Short for 'nach Hause.' 'Heimgehen' (to go home), 'Heimweh' (homesickness), 'Heimat' (homeland). 'Heim' is one of the most emotionally loaded words in German."},
        {type:"tip",title:"Five Affixes That Change Everything",text:"[AR] Five prefixes and compounds that multiply your vocabulary:\n\n1. miss- (wrong): Missverständnis = misunderstanding, Misstrauen = mistrust\n2. schwieger- (in-law): Schwiegermutter = mother-in-law, Schwiegervater = father-in-law\n3. un- (not): unglaublich = unbelievable, unheimlich = uncanny\n4. vorbei- (past): vorbeigehen = to walk past, vorbeikommen = to come by\n5. weg- (away): weggehen = to go away, wegnehmen = to take away\n\nEvery word you already know can be modified with these affixes.",deepDive:{title:"Separable vs. Inseparable Prefixes",text:"[AR] Separable prefixes (stressed, split off):\nvorbei-: Er geht vorbei. / Er ist vorbeigegangen.\nweg-: Sie geht weg. / Sie ist weggegangen.\n\nInseparable prefixes (unstressed, stay attached):\nmiss-: Er missversteht mich. / Er hat mich missverstanden.\n\nCompound forms:\nschwieger-: always written together, never split.\nun-: always together with adjectives and nouns."}},
        {type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"resolution",art:"de-ber-stairwell-pickles",trg:"Am nächsten Morgen fand Verumius ein Glas Gurken vor seiner Tür. Auf dem Zettel stand: 'Von Ihrem Nachbarn. Frieden?'",src:"[AR] The next morning Verumius found a jar of pickles at his door. The note read: 'From your neighbor. Peace?'"},
        {type:"mc",q:"Nachdem Verumius lange nachgedacht hatte, stellte er ein Glas Marmelade vor die Tür. Was bedeutet 'nachdem' hier?",opts:[
            "Zeitliche Reihenfolge: zuerst nachdenken, dann handeln",
            "Gleichzeitigkeit: nachdenken und handeln zur gleichen Zeit",
            "Kontrast: obwohl er nachgedacht hat",
            "Bedingung: nur wenn er nachgedacht hat"
          ],ans:"Zeitliche Reihenfolge: zuerst nachdenken, dann handeln",hint:"[AR] 'Nachdem' orders events in time: the earlier event (Plusquamperfekt) happens BEFORE the later one."},
        {type:"fb",s:"Könnten Sie mir sagen, {1} der Nachbar die Gurken gebracht hat?",a:["wann"],opts:["wann","ob","dass","weil"],hint:"[AR] The question asks about the time of delivery. Which W-word fits?",sSrc:"[AR] Could you tell me when the neighbor brought the pickles?"},
        {type:"drag_fill",s:"Nachdem er die Marmelade {1} hatte, wollte der Nachbar wissen, {2} Verumius wirklich so nett {3}.",blanks:{"1":"probiert","2":"ob","3":"war"},pool:["probiert","ob","war","gegessen","dass","ist"],hint:"[AR] Three blanks: the tasting verb (Partizip II), the yes/no connector, and the past state of being. Nachdem + Plusquamperfekt structure.",sSrc:"[AR] After he had tasted the jam, the neighbor wanted to know whether Verumius was really that nice."},
        {type:"match",pairs:[
            {trg:"Gegner",src:"opponent"},
            {trg:"Langeweile",src:"boredom"},
            {trg:"stumm",src:"mute/silent"},
            {trg:"unglaublich",src:"unbelievable"},
            {trg:"beißen",src:"to bite"},
            {trg:"bestrafen",src:"to punish"}
          ]}
      ]}
  ]};

export default UNIT_16_AR;
